WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.259 --> 00:00:05.259
&gt;&gt; I’m Jeff Bezos.

00:00:05.259 --> 00:00:06.669
&gt;&gt; What is your claim to fame?

00:00:06.669 --> 00:00:07.669
&gt;&gt; I’m the founder of

00:00:07.669 --> 00:00:08.669
Amazon.com.

00:00:08.669 --> 00:00:09.669
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: From the

00:00:09.669 --> 00:00:11.379
award-winning producers of “The
Facebook Dilemma”.

00:00:11.379 --> 00:00:13.879
&gt;&gt; Richest guy in the world.

00:00:13.879 --> 00:00:15.080
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: FRONTLINE

00:00:15.080 --> 00:00:16.369
investigates Amazon.

00:00:16.369 --> 00:00:19.820
&gt;&gt; Is Amazon taking over the

00:00:19.820 --> 00:00:21.200
world a good thing?

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:22.200
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Questioning those

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:23.200
who run the company...

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:24.200
&gt;&gt; What would you say to someone

00:00:24.200 --> 00:00:26.860
who feels as though humans are
increasingly being treated like

00:00:26.860 --> 00:00:27.860
robots?

00:00:27.860 --> 00:00:28.860
&gt;&gt; That’s not the experience

00:00:28.860 --> 00:00:30.070
that I had in setting it up.

00:00:30.070 --> 00:00:31.640
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: And those no longer

00:00:31.640 --> 00:00:32.640
there.

00:00:32.640 --> 00:00:33.640
&gt;&gt; Most people would assume

00:00:33.640 --> 00:00:35.780
there’s a pretty high safety
standard on Amazon.

00:00:35.780 --> 00:00:36.780
&gt;&gt; And that assumption would be
incorrect.

00:00:36.780 --> 00:00:39.809
&gt;&gt; The tools are not what I call
battle tested.

00:00:39.809 --> 00:00:41.920
&gt;&gt; Some people asking if Amazon
is a monopoly.

00:00:41.920 --> 00:00:46.609
&gt;&gt; The question for the
democracy is, are we okay with

00:00:46.609 --> 00:00:49.019
one company essentially winning
capitalism?

00:00:49.019 --> 00:00:52.420
&gt;&gt; How do you and
Jeff think about the call to

00:00:52.420 --> 00:00:53.770
break you guys up?

00:00:53.770 --> 00:00:54.770
&gt;&gt; Simply because the

00:00:54.770 --> 00:00:56.670
company’s been
successful doesn’t mean it’s

00:00:56.670 --> 00:00:57.849
somehow too big.

00:00:57.849 --> 00:00:59.030
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Now on

00:00:59.030 --> 00:01:00.030
FRONTLINE...

00:01:00.030 --> 00:01:01.030
&gt;&gt; Domination was very much the

00:01:01.030 --> 00:01:02.030
idea.

00:01:02.030 --> 00:01:04.319
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: “Amazon Empire”.

00:01:04.319 --> 00:01:09.260
&gt;&gt; Jeff Bezos has already
conquered the retail frontier.

00:01:09.260 --> 00:01:11.080
Now he's got a plan to colonize
the planets.

00:01:11.080 --> 00:01:13.360
&gt;&gt; Bezos is laying out his plans
for colonizing space.

00:01:13.360 --> 00:01:16.870
&gt;&gt; Bezos is known for going big,
and now he's literally shooting

00:01:16.870 --> 00:01:18.110
for the moon.

00:01:18.110 --> 00:01:19.570
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: In May of 2019,

00:01:19.570 --> 00:01:22.550
Jeff Bezos, the richest person
on the planet, unveiled his

00:01:22.550 --> 00:01:25.640
latest invention.

00:01:25.640 --> 00:01:28.030
&gt;&gt; This is Blue Moon.

00:01:28.030 --> 00:01:31.740
It's time to go back to the
moon, this time to stay.

00:01:31.740 --> 00:01:34.270
&gt;&gt; Jeff has said over and over
again that the most important

00:01:34.270 --> 00:01:37.230
work he's doing is work in
space.

00:01:37.230 --> 00:01:40.670
What he's built in Amazon is
really important and really

00:01:40.670 --> 00:01:44.640
interesting, and it's, it's
revolutionized commerce.

00:01:44.640 --> 00:01:47.070
But it's only revolutionized
commerce.

00:01:47.070 --> 00:01:50.780
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Bezos's plan is to
chart a new course for the

00:01:50.780 --> 00:01:52.420
future of humanity.

00:01:52.420 --> 00:01:55.140
&gt;&gt; Manufactured worlds rotated

00:01:55.140 --> 00:01:58.710
to create artificial gravity
with centrifugal force.

00:01:58.710 --> 00:02:02.031
These are very large structures,
miles on end.

00:02:02.031 --> 00:02:04.940
And they hold a million people
or more each.

00:02:04.940 --> 00:02:08.259
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: It's an idea he's
had since he was a teenager.

00:02:08.259 --> 00:02:11.420
&gt;&gt; This is me in high school.

00:02:11.420 --> 00:02:12.420
And I want to highlight this

00:02:12.420 --> 00:02:16.590
quote: "The earth is finite, and
if the world economy and

00:02:16.590 --> 00:02:21.599
population is to keep expanding,
space is the only way to go."

00:02:21.599 --> 00:02:23.299
I still believe that.

00:02:23.299 --> 00:02:24.830
&gt;&gt; The way Jeff Bezos sees is it

00:02:24.830 --> 00:02:30.129
is that consumerism is an
example of how today's society

00:02:30.129 --> 00:02:33.280
lives better than our parents
did and our grandparents.

00:02:33.280 --> 00:02:37.099
And he wants, you know, future
generations to continue to have

00:02:37.099 --> 00:02:39.029
an increasingly better
lifestyle.

00:02:39.029 --> 00:02:41.749
&gt;&gt; These are beautiful.

00:02:41.749 --> 00:02:43.010
People are going to want to live

00:02:43.010 --> 00:02:44.010
here.

00:02:44.010 --> 00:02:45.329
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Bezos unveiled his

00:02:45.329 --> 00:02:48.720
extra-terrestrial plans at a
time of growing concern about

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:52.459
the empire he's built here on
earth.

00:02:52.459 --> 00:02:54.880
&gt;&gt; Amazon is the great
disrupter, from books to retail

00:02:54.880 --> 00:02:55.880
to grocery stores.

00:02:55.880 --> 00:02:57.159
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: For more than 25

00:02:57.159 --> 00:03:00.920
years, Jeff Bezos has been
disrupting and transforming

00:03:00.920 --> 00:03:04.099
almost every aspect of our
modern lives.

00:03:04.099 --> 00:03:07.379
&gt;&gt; Once you start connecting the
dots, you see that Amazon is

00:03:07.379 --> 00:03:10.930
building all of the invisible
infrastructure for our futures.

00:03:10.930 --> 00:03:13.030
&gt;&gt; Amazon announced a healthcare
partnership...

00:03:13.030 --> 00:03:15.129
&gt;&gt; Amazon is helping the C.I.A.
build a secure cloud...

00:03:15.129 --> 00:03:16.959
&gt;&gt; How much of the internet do
you run?

00:03:16.959 --> 00:03:20.479
&gt;&gt; That's a good question, um,
it's a lot, though.

00:03:20.479 --> 00:03:23.700
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: But in recent
years, Amazon-- and Bezos-- have

00:03:23.700 --> 00:03:28.150
come under scrutiny for their
aggressive tactics and expanding

00:03:28.150 --> 00:03:29.519
power.

00:03:29.519 --> 00:03:32.249
(Bezos laughing)

00:03:32.249 --> 00:03:37.040
&gt;&gt; Everything that is admirable
about Amazon is also something

00:03:37.040 --> 00:03:39.629
that we should fear about it.

00:03:39.629 --> 00:03:42.930
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: For the past year,

00:03:42.930 --> 00:03:45.871
we've been investigating how
Jeff Bezos built his empire--

00:03:45.871 --> 00:03:48.459
and at what cost.

00:03:48.459 --> 00:03:52.079
&gt;&gt; And so think about this.

00:03:52.079 --> 00:03:57.029
Big things start small.

00:03:57.029 --> 00:03:58.029
♪ ♪

00:03:58.029 --> 00:04:10.620
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Jeff Bezos's empire
has its roots not in Silicon

00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:13.430
Valley, but on Wall Street.

00:04:13.430 --> 00:04:14.430
That's where the young Princeton

00:04:14.430 --> 00:04:18.010
graduate went to work in the
early 1990s, at a secretive

00:04:18.010 --> 00:04:20.380
hedge fund called D.E.

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:21.650
Shaw.

00:04:21.650 --> 00:04:25.880
&gt;&gt; David Shaw was the one who
revolutionized Wall Street by

00:04:25.880 --> 00:04:28.070
introducing data.

00:04:28.070 --> 00:04:30.470
And I think Jeff really embraced

00:04:30.470 --> 00:04:34.921
that, that idea that, "Hey, if
you have data, ultimately, you

00:04:34.921 --> 00:04:38.650
win."

00:04:38.650 --> 00:04:39.650
&gt;&gt; One of the things that David

00:04:39.650 --> 00:04:42.980
Shaw asked Jeff Bezos to do was
to go and investigate new

00:04:42.980 --> 00:04:45.880
businesses, and in particular
this new thing in the early

00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:47.750
'90s called the World Wide Web.

00:04:47.750 --> 00:04:49.220
(dial-up modem connecting)

00:04:49.220 --> 00:04:51.310
&gt;&gt; We all know that a
communications revolution is

00:04:51.310 --> 00:04:52.500
underway in this country.

00:04:52.500 --> 00:04:53.560
&gt;&gt; What is the internet?

00:04:53.560 --> 00:04:55.720
&gt;&gt; It's sort of the mother of
all networks.

00:04:55.720 --> 00:04:57.500
&gt;&gt; It's information highways.

00:04:57.500 --> 00:04:59.060
&gt;&gt; It's kind of like your remote

00:04:59.060 --> 00:05:00.660
control to the world.

00:05:00.660 --> 00:05:02.560
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Bezos was quick to

00:05:02.560 --> 00:05:06.510
see the untapped potential of
the new digital landscape and

00:05:06.510 --> 00:05:08.759
was determined to get in on it.

00:05:08.759 --> 00:05:10.780
&gt;&gt; I came across this startling

00:05:10.780 --> 00:05:14.080
statistic that web usage was
growing at 2,300% a year.

00:05:14.080 --> 00:05:18.030
So, I decided I would try and
find a business plan that made

00:05:18.030 --> 00:05:21.250
sense in the context of that
growth, and I picked books as

00:05:21.250 --> 00:05:28.150
the first best product to sell
online.

00:05:28.150 --> 00:05:29.150
♪ ♪
Because books are incredibly

00:05:29.150 --> 00:05:32.010
unusual in one respect, and
that is that there are more

00:05:32.010 --> 00:05:35.530
items in the book category than
there are items in any other

00:05:35.530 --> 00:05:36.620
category by far.

00:05:36.620 --> 00:05:38.420
So, when you have that many

00:05:38.420 --> 00:05:42.840
items, you can literally build a
store online that couldn't exist

00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:44.070
any other way.

00:05:44.070 --> 00:05:45.721
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: The store he was

00:05:45.721 --> 00:05:55.000
imagining didn't exist, so he
decided to build it himself.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:56.650
♪ ♪
&gt;&gt; The reaction to Jeff's idea

00:05:56.650 --> 00:06:00.670
to start selling books on the
internet was pretty incredulous,

00:06:00.670 --> 00:06:02.340
you know, from a lot of the
people close to him.

00:06:02.340 --> 00:06:05.650
His mom tried to convince him to
just do it at night or over the

00:06:05.650 --> 00:06:06.650
weekends.

00:06:06.650 --> 00:06:07.650
She didn't want to see him give

00:06:07.650 --> 00:06:12.310
up his job.

00:06:12.310 --> 00:06:13.610
&gt;&gt; Jeff called, and he told me

00:06:13.610 --> 00:06:16.040
that he and MacKenzie were
quitting their jobs, and they

00:06:16.040 --> 00:06:17.660
were moving to Seattle and
starting a company.

00:06:17.660 --> 00:06:18.660
I said, "Great, well, what are
you going to do?"

00:06:18.660 --> 00:06:20.980
He said, "We're going to sell
books."

00:06:20.980 --> 00:06:23.330
I said, "Nice."

00:06:23.330 --> 00:06:25.780
He said, "On the internet."

00:06:25.780 --> 00:06:26.780
I said, "Oh.

00:06:26.780 --> 00:06:27.780
Jeff, why will anybody buy

00:06:27.780 --> 00:06:28.780
anything from you?"

00:06:28.780 --> 00:06:29.780
And he said, "Well, we're going

00:06:29.780 --> 00:06:31.960
to have more books than anybody
else."

00:06:31.960 --> 00:06:36.620
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: One of the first
names Bezos considered for his

00:06:36.620 --> 00:06:39.750
new website was Relentless.com.

00:06:39.750 --> 00:06:42.021
&gt;&gt; Why "Relentless?"

00:06:42.021 --> 00:06:45.450
&gt;&gt; Relentless meant, "We move on
no matter what."

00:06:45.450 --> 00:06:49.430
He ultimately, obviously,
decided that "Relentless" wasn't

00:06:49.430 --> 00:06:50.960
quite the right fit.

00:06:50.960 --> 00:06:53.930
Amazon, earth's largest river,

00:06:53.930 --> 00:06:54.930
was.

00:06:54.930 --> 00:06:57.280
Amazon means gigantic.

00:06:57.280 --> 00:07:00.180
&gt;&gt; In terms of
relentlessness, stopping at

00:07:00.180 --> 00:07:05.200
nothing, that's, is that an apt
description of Jeff?

00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:07.080
&gt;&gt; No.

00:07:07.080 --> 00:07:08.440
It's not that Jeff stops at

00:07:08.440 --> 00:07:12.540
nothing, it's that when Jeff
sets his mind on a goal that he

00:07:12.540 --> 00:07:18.060
thinks he can achieve, he won't
stop until he's proven wrong

00:07:18.060 --> 00:07:22.889
or until he achieves it.

00:07:22.889 --> 00:07:23.889
♪ ♪

00:07:23.889 --> 00:07:26.180
&gt;&gt; Jeff and MacKenzie had rented
a house in Bellevue.

00:07:26.180 --> 00:07:29.670
And then we moved to a small,
second-floor office in the

00:07:29.670 --> 00:07:31.229
south part of Seattle.

00:07:31.229 --> 00:07:32.830
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Shel Kaphan was

00:07:32.830 --> 00:07:38.890
Amazon employee number one, one
of nine former Amazon insiders

00:07:38.890 --> 00:07:41.310
who agreed to talk on camera.

00:07:41.310 --> 00:07:42.800
&gt;&gt; What the company is now was

00:07:42.800 --> 00:07:45.740
nowhere in my wildest
imagination.

00:07:45.740 --> 00:07:51.000
Nowhere, so, the fact that it
could have the-the kind of

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:55.030
position in the world that it
has now, I had no clue.

00:07:55.030 --> 00:08:02.900
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: In July 1995,
Amazon.com went live.

00:08:02.900 --> 00:08:07.310
&gt;&gt; It was an incredible novelty,
it was tiny and obscure, and

00:08:07.310 --> 00:08:10.860
it's very hard to imagine, but
the entire universe that Amazon

00:08:10.860 --> 00:08:13.860
now dominates did not exist.

00:08:13.860 --> 00:08:15.310
&gt;&gt; Amazon.com, this virtual

00:08:15.310 --> 00:08:18.060
shop claims to be the world's
largest bookstore.

00:08:18.060 --> 00:08:21.700
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: It didn't take long
for Bezos's vision to prove

00:08:21.700 --> 00:08:22.700
prescient.

00:08:22.700 --> 00:08:23.940
&gt;&gt; What makes us different is

00:08:23.940 --> 00:08:27.389
vast selection, convenience-- we
deliver right to the desktop.

00:08:27.389 --> 00:08:30.440
If our catalog were printed on
paper, it would be the size of

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:34.000
seven New York City phonebooks.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:35.000
♪ ♪

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:39.320
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: The company quickly
outgrew the garage and soon had

00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:41.360
more than 50 employees.

00:08:41.360 --> 00:08:44.580
In 1996, James Marcus applied to

00:08:44.580 --> 00:08:48.240
be number 55.

00:08:48.240 --> 00:08:49.240
&gt;&gt; There was a very palpable

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:53.520
excitement in the air at this
place, and of course at this

00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:56.430
point Jeff Bezos was the first
person to interview every

00:08:56.430 --> 00:08:57.990
prospective employee.

00:08:57.990 --> 00:08:59.640
So I was ushered into his

00:08:59.640 --> 00:09:00.640
office.

00:09:00.640 --> 00:09:02.570
He wanted to see how fast you

00:09:02.570 --> 00:09:03.760
were on your feet.

00:09:03.760 --> 00:09:04.810
He also always wanted to know

00:09:04.810 --> 00:09:06.339
your S.A.T. scores.

00:09:06.339 --> 00:09:07.430
&gt;&gt; He wanted to know

00:09:07.430 --> 00:09:08.430
your S.A.T. scores?

00:09:08.430 --> 00:09:09.430
&gt;&gt; Every time, yes.

00:09:09.430 --> 00:09:10.769
&gt;&gt; How old were you at
the time?

00:09:10.769 --> 00:09:13.440
&gt;&gt; I was 36 or 37.

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:15.390
&gt;&gt; This is the original sign

00:09:15.390 --> 00:09:16.960
that I made for Amazon.com.

00:09:16.960 --> 00:09:20.480
Blue spray paint on white poster

00:09:20.480 --> 00:09:21.480
board.

00:09:21.480 --> 00:09:22.640
&gt;&gt; Jeff wasn't a figure out of

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:25.520
folklore at that point, he was
not the-the wealthiest man in

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:26.520
the world.

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:27.860
&gt;&gt; Here's my computer,

00:09:27.860 --> 00:09:30.040
Amazon.com up on the screen.

00:09:30.040 --> 00:09:32.779
"Hello, Jeff Bezos."

00:09:32.779 --> 00:09:35.870
&gt;&gt; He was a small, nondescript,
sandy-haired man sitting at a

00:09:35.870 --> 00:09:40.880
desk with quite a large and
eruptive laugh.

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:47.020
(laughing in multiple scenes)
&gt;&gt; But he wasn't threatening, he

00:09:47.020 --> 00:09:50.329
was a normal guy to a sort of
amazing extent.

00:09:50.329 --> 00:09:54.150
&gt;&gt; HAL 9000 hat, very important.

00:09:54.150 --> 00:09:56.090
Hal and I share a birthday,

00:09:56.090 --> 00:09:57.400
we're both born on January 12.

00:09:57.400 --> 00:10:00.220
&gt;&gt; It belied, you know, an

00:10:00.220 --> 00:10:02.140
enormous, Napoleonic ambition.

00:10:02.140 --> 00:10:03.640
&gt;&gt; One of the people I really

00:10:03.640 --> 00:10:07.140
like, Thomas Edison, here's a
model of his original light

00:10:07.140 --> 00:10:08.140
bulb.

00:10:08.140 --> 00:10:10.120
He's famous for saying, "One

00:10:10.120 --> 00:10:13.110
percent inspiration, 99 percent
perspiration."

00:10:13.110 --> 00:10:16.870
(laughs)
It turns out ideas are the easy

00:10:16.870 --> 00:10:18.920
part, execution is everything.

00:10:18.920 --> 00:10:19.920
&gt;&gt; Domination was on Jeff's mind

00:10:19.920 --> 00:10:20.920
from the beginning.

00:10:20.920 --> 00:10:21.920
One of his sort of

00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:24.550
second-in-command people said
to me, "You have to understand

00:10:24.550 --> 00:10:28.040
that Jeff wants to sell many
more things than books.

00:10:28.040 --> 00:10:31.200
And Jeff's idea is that in the
near-distant future, you could

00:10:31.200 --> 00:10:33.180
buy a kayak from Amazon.

00:10:33.180 --> 00:10:34.300
And if, and after you brought

00:10:34.300 --> 00:10:37.610
the kayak, you could figure out
good places to kayak and buy

00:10:37.610 --> 00:10:39.880
travel services from Amazon."

00:10:39.880 --> 00:10:41.800
So, those ambitions were very

00:10:41.800 --> 00:10:44.830
clear, and this was very early
on.

00:10:44.830 --> 00:10:47.000
But he was clearly thinking in
those terms from the get-go.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:49.650
&gt;&gt; How did that ring to
you at the time?

00:10:49.650 --> 00:10:53.209
&gt;&gt; A little bit exciting and a
little bit nutty.

00:10:53.209 --> 00:10:54.850
&gt;&gt; Amazon.com, very good
website.

00:10:54.850 --> 00:10:57.110
You should really try it.

00:10:57.110 --> 00:10:59.569
(Bezos laughs)

00:10:59.569 --> 00:11:02.839
&gt;&gt; If you signed on to work at
a-a kind of futuristic

00:11:02.839 --> 00:11:06.140
bookstore, and the guy who
owned it was suddenly talking

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:10.050
about selling, you know, every
object in the universe, you just

00:11:10.050 --> 00:11:12.500
weren't sure how seriously to
take it.

00:11:12.500 --> 00:11:17.740
(Bezos laughing)
(Bezos screaming playfully)

00:11:17.740 --> 00:11:23.000
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Though his public
image was often unserious...

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:24.450
&gt;&gt; That was awesome!

00:11:24.450 --> 00:11:26.440
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Inside the company,

00:11:26.440 --> 00:11:30.089
Bezos was a hard-charging
manager relentlessly focused on

00:11:30.089 --> 00:11:32.820
the principle that would make
Amazon one of the most trusted

00:11:32.820 --> 00:11:38.040
brands in the world: the
customer always comes first.

00:11:38.040 --> 00:11:40.029
&gt;&gt; This culture of customer
obsession...

00:11:40.029 --> 00:11:41.950
Obsessive focus on customer...

00:11:41.950 --> 00:11:43.620
Obsesses over our customers...

00:11:43.620 --> 00:11:47.829
Totally obsessing over the
customer experience.

00:11:47.829 --> 00:11:49.700
&gt;&gt; We used to call it customer
ecstasy.

00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:54.500
It means building, delivering,
focusing on your customer.

00:11:54.500 --> 00:11:57.839
And we did it, you know, in the
very, very early days at every

00:11:57.839 --> 00:11:58.839
stage.

00:11:58.839 --> 00:12:00.700
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Jennifer Cast was

00:12:00.700 --> 00:12:05.089
there in the early days and is
one of six top Amazon executives

00:12:05.089 --> 00:12:08.510
the company put forward to
speak to us.

00:12:08.510 --> 00:12:12.100
&gt;&gt; Customer obsession was our
North Star.

00:12:12.100 --> 00:12:15.160
And so, you know, it was a place
where we knew we were a part of

00:12:15.160 --> 00:12:19.089
something that was new, the
internet.

00:12:19.089 --> 00:12:21.529
There was an excitement that we
were doing something that hadn't

00:12:21.529 --> 00:12:22.529
been done before.

00:12:22.529 --> 00:12:24.580
It was exhilarating.

00:12:24.580 --> 00:12:28.420
We were all aligned around
building for customers.

00:12:28.420 --> 00:12:30.250
&gt;&gt; Hey, you guys.

00:12:30.250 --> 00:12:31.250
&gt;&gt; Hey.

00:12:31.250 --> 00:12:33.050
(Bezos laughs)
&gt;&gt; I've heard there was

00:12:33.050 --> 00:12:36.410
an empty chair that would often
be put at meetings.

00:12:36.410 --> 00:12:37.410
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:12:37.410 --> 00:12:38.410
&gt;&gt; Who was in the empty

00:12:38.410 --> 00:12:39.410
chair?

00:12:39.410 --> 00:12:40.410
&gt;&gt; Yeah, so that empty chair was

00:12:40.410 --> 00:12:43.500
there to remind us all to
understand the customer, have

00:12:43.500 --> 00:12:46.350
empathy for the customer,
understand the details of the

00:12:46.350 --> 00:12:47.380
customer experience.

00:12:47.380 --> 00:12:49.589
The customer isn't there, we

00:12:49.589 --> 00:12:51.860
have to bring forward the voice
of the customer.

00:12:51.860 --> 00:12:54.900
(phone ringing)
&gt;&gt; Thank you for calling

00:12:54.900 --> 00:12:55.900
Amazon.com.

00:12:55.900 --> 00:12:56.900
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: And Bezos quickly

00:12:56.900 --> 00:13:01.830
learned that in this new online
world, he could understand

00:13:01.830 --> 00:13:04.550
exactly how customers were
behaving.

00:13:04.550 --> 00:13:06.980
&gt;&gt; All orders do need to be
placed online.

00:13:06.980 --> 00:13:09.550
&gt;&gt; It was made clear from the
beginning that data collection

00:13:09.550 --> 00:13:12.290
was also one of Amazon's
businesses.

00:13:12.290 --> 00:13:14.399
All customer behavior that
flowed through the site was

00:13:14.399 --> 00:13:16.300
recorded and tracked.

00:13:16.300 --> 00:13:17.620
And that itself was a valuable

00:13:17.620 --> 00:13:18.620
commodity.

00:13:18.620 --> 00:13:20.290
&gt;&gt; Have you visited our website?

00:13:20.290 --> 00:13:24.730
&gt;&gt; We could track how a customer
navigated through the site.

00:13:24.730 --> 00:13:27.370
So we could see what you looked
at, we could also see what you

00:13:27.370 --> 00:13:30.610
paused at, we could see what you
put in your basket but didn't

00:13:30.610 --> 00:13:33.430
order, we could see what you put
in your basket and did order.

00:13:33.430 --> 00:13:35.610
So that's when we started
realizing, "Man, this is rich.

00:13:35.610 --> 00:13:37.130
This is rich, rich, rich."

00:13:37.130 --> 00:13:38.390
And so we've used it for

00:13:38.390 --> 00:13:39.390
everything.

00:13:39.390 --> 00:13:40.390
&gt;&gt; What do you do with that

00:13:40.390 --> 00:13:41.390
information?

00:13:41.390 --> 00:13:42.790
&gt;&gt; That's the data that allows

00:13:42.790 --> 00:13:46.790
us to predict, or try to
predict, what books that you

00:13:46.790 --> 00:13:49.230
would like that you haven't
discovered yet.

00:13:49.230 --> 00:13:53.090
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Bezos treated the
site as a laboratory, where he

00:13:53.090 --> 00:13:57.300
studied customer behavior along
with his chief scientist Andreas

00:13:57.300 --> 00:13:59.080
Weigend.

00:13:59.080 --> 00:14:01.149
&gt;&gt; I was shocked to see how

00:14:01.149 --> 00:14:02.940
predictable people are.

00:14:02.940 --> 00:14:06.340
If you take the time of the day

00:14:06.340 --> 00:14:10.750
into account, if you take maybe
when they were last on the site,

00:14:10.750 --> 00:14:13.490
how long they were on the site
last time, how long they're on

00:14:13.490 --> 00:14:17.850
the site today, you know what
they're falling for.

00:14:17.850 --> 00:14:24.000
&gt;&gt; Whoever owns, collects, the
data, if you have access to it

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:27.190
and rights to data, then you are
king.

00:14:27.190 --> 00:14:30.760
It's all about the data.

00:14:30.760 --> 00:14:33.150
Everything.

00:14:33.150 --> 00:14:35.830
&gt;&gt; One of the most fascinating
kind of tools we have at our

00:14:35.830 --> 00:14:39.560
disposal is the ability to do
active experiments.

00:14:39.560 --> 00:14:43.899
It's, you know, it's kind of
this huge laboratory.

00:14:43.899 --> 00:14:47.000
&gt;&gt; We did not think about it as
exploiting, we thought about

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.329
helping people make better
decisions.

00:14:50.329 --> 00:14:53.149
&gt;&gt; I was starting to feel that
that was less respectful toward

00:14:53.149 --> 00:14:56.480
the consumer, who was, after
all, supposed to be our god, the

00:14:56.480 --> 00:15:00.720
person whose ecstasy was our
very reason for being.

00:15:00.720 --> 00:15:04.350
And it was closer to getting a
cow into a milking stall and

00:15:04.350 --> 00:15:07.610
extracting as many pails as
possible during each visit.

00:15:07.610 --> 00:15:09.490
And that felt a little more
unsavory.

00:15:09.490 --> 00:15:13.040
But that was the business of
Amazon.

00:15:13.040 --> 00:15:15.640
&gt;&gt; Amazon has added 880,000 new
customers...

00:15:15.640 --> 00:15:18.860
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: While Bezos was
using these insights to bring

00:15:18.860 --> 00:15:21.420
more and more customers into
Amazon...

00:15:21.420 --> 00:15:23.370
&gt;&gt; The number of customers who
use the website has increased

00:15:23.370 --> 00:15:24.370
fourfold...

00:15:24.370 --> 00:15:25.370
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: There was one thing

00:15:25.370 --> 00:15:27.970
he hadn't done yet.

00:15:27.970 --> 00:15:28.990
&gt;&gt; The company's never made a

00:15:28.990 --> 00:15:29.990
profit.

00:15:29.990 --> 00:15:30.990
&gt;&gt; That's right.

00:15:30.990 --> 00:15:33.760
&gt;&gt; Now, why... how does that...
why... how does that...?

00:15:33.760 --> 00:15:35.400
&gt;&gt; It seems like a new math,
doesn't it?

00:15:35.400 --> 00:15:36.400
&gt;&gt; It does.

00:15:36.400 --> 00:15:37.400
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Bezos would spend

00:15:37.400 --> 00:15:42.679
years losing money trying to
beat his competition, and he

00:15:42.679 --> 00:15:47.089
convinced investors to go along
with it.

00:15:47.089 --> 00:15:51.000
&gt;&gt; One of Jeff Bezos' greatest
accomplishments has been his

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:54.810
ability to get Wall Street to
accept the fact the first

00:15:54.810 --> 00:15:57.560
20-some years, Amazon wasn't
going to be very profitable.

00:15:57.560 --> 00:15:59.760
And that's okay because they're
building infrastructure that

00:15:59.760 --> 00:16:03.811
will create huge opportunities
for them to gain scale and gain

00:16:03.811 --> 00:16:05.490
customers and gain business.

00:16:05.490 --> 00:16:07.170
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: He spelled it out

00:16:07.170 --> 00:16:10.709
in a letter to shareholders
after the company first went

00:16:10.709 --> 00:16:16.140
public: "It's all about the
long term," he wrote, rather

00:16:16.140 --> 00:16:18.770
than short-term profits or Wall
Street reactions.

00:16:18.770 --> 00:16:25.180
&gt;&gt; He essentially says,
"We are going to forego profits

00:16:25.180 --> 00:16:26.760
in order to take market share.

00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:28.860
That our strategy is to lose

00:16:28.860 --> 00:16:32.670
money, which enables us then to
put other companies out of

00:16:32.670 --> 00:16:34.740
business who can't afford to
lose money."

00:16:34.740 --> 00:16:37.420
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: That strategy
wouldn't sit well with critics

00:16:37.420 --> 00:16:41.540
like Stacy Mitchell, who
advocates for small businesses.

00:16:41.540 --> 00:16:43.910
&gt;&gt; In essence, at the very
beginning, he's signaling to

00:16:43.910 --> 00:16:47.970
shareholders, "I have a strategy
to monopolize the market, and

00:16:47.970 --> 00:16:51.250
that's going to reward you, but
it's going to be far down the

00:16:51.250 --> 00:16:52.740
road, and will you come along
with me?"

00:16:52.740 --> 00:16:55.400
And they said yes.

00:16:55.400 --> 00:16:56.730
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Investors also

00:16:56.730 --> 00:17:02.750
recognized Bezos' essential
advantage over physical stores,

00:17:02.750 --> 00:17:05.579
which had to charge their
customers sales tax, unlike

00:17:05.579 --> 00:17:07.160
online businesses.

00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:09.420
&gt;&gt; So, not collecting sales tax

00:17:09.420 --> 00:17:13.309
gave Amazon a big leg up over
bricks and mortar retailers.

00:17:13.309 --> 00:17:16.430
And that was central to their
early strategy of gaining

00:17:16.430 --> 00:17:18.680
market share as quickly as they
can.

00:17:18.680 --> 00:17:21.120
&gt;&gt; What booksellers were saying
to me is that, "This is driving

00:17:21.120 --> 00:17:22.309
my customers to Amazon.

00:17:22.309 --> 00:17:23.709
They'll come into the store,

00:17:23.709 --> 00:17:25.850
they'll browse, they find what
they want, but then they'll go

00:17:25.850 --> 00:17:30.149
buy it on Amazon, because they
can save that sales tax."

00:17:30.149 --> 00:17:33.610
&gt;&gt; So it was a very irksome,
early, big issue for the book

00:17:33.610 --> 00:17:35.620
vendors, first of all, they were
kind of the canaries in the

00:17:35.620 --> 00:17:39.259
mine, so to speak, and then lots
of other retailers.

00:17:39.259 --> 00:17:42.220
♪ ♪
&gt;&gt; Amazon has added thousands of

00:17:42.220 --> 00:17:45.120
warehouse workers and three
million square feet of space.

00:17:45.120 --> 00:17:48.260
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Amazon's sales-tax
advantage would be central to

00:17:48.260 --> 00:17:52.390
its success as it expanded
beyond books, into other

00:17:52.390 --> 00:17:53.390
products.

00:17:53.390 --> 00:17:54.390
&gt;&gt; And we have a fantastic

00:17:54.390 --> 00:17:55.830
selection of things you can
look at.

00:17:55.830 --> 00:17:57.710
Electronics and then of course
toys.

00:17:57.710 --> 00:18:01.370
Yeah, thank you, here is, we've
got have the friendly Pokémon.

00:18:01.370 --> 00:18:05.050
This is more than ten times the
selection that you will find in

00:18:05.050 --> 00:18:07.120
a typical, physical world
software store.

00:18:07.120 --> 00:18:10.020
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: But Bezos was still
a long way from his goal of

00:18:10.020 --> 00:18:13.890
Amazon being the place where you
could buy everything online.

00:18:13.890 --> 00:18:21.710
(drills whirring)
And he saw a way to achieve it.

00:18:21.710 --> 00:18:24.200
&gt;&gt; Amazon could soon become the
Walmart of the internet.

00:18:24.200 --> 00:18:26.500
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: There were
thousands of businesses eager to

00:18:26.500 --> 00:18:27.500
sell online.

00:18:27.500 --> 00:18:29.630
Bezos offered them a way to do

00:18:29.630 --> 00:18:30.630
it.

00:18:30.630 --> 00:18:31.809
&gt;&gt; Amazon is transforming itself

00:18:31.809 --> 00:18:34.509
from an online bookstore to an
online mall.

00:18:34.509 --> 00:18:37.880
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: He transformed
Amazon into a retail platform

00:18:37.880 --> 00:18:41.640
where anyone could sell their
goods to his customers and

00:18:41.640 --> 00:18:44.610
invited thousands of other
businesses to be a part of it.

00:18:44.610 --> 00:18:48.990
&gt;&gt; It's the easiest place for
anybody, small or large, who

00:18:48.990 --> 00:18:52.299
wants to set up shop online to
sell online, because they can

00:18:52.299 --> 00:18:55.540
access our 12 million-plus
customers.

00:18:55.540 --> 00:18:59.309
Anybody, all comers.

00:18:59.309 --> 00:19:00.380
&gt;&gt; We're talking about hundreds

00:19:00.380 --> 00:19:03.070
of thousands of companies with
literally tens of millions of

00:19:03.070 --> 00:19:04.960
products.

00:19:04.960 --> 00:19:07.350
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Name-brand stores

00:19:07.350 --> 00:19:11.170
started selling on Bezos's
platform, and so did tens of

00:19:11.170 --> 00:19:15.370
thousands of small
entrepreneurs.

00:19:15.370 --> 00:19:17.620
&gt;&gt; Everyone knew Amazon.com.

00:19:17.620 --> 00:19:18.620
The only people that knew

00:19:18.620 --> 00:19:21.380
SuperDuperHoops.com were the
ones that were searching to buy

00:19:21.380 --> 00:19:24.890
a basketball hoop and saw our
name on an advertisement.

00:19:24.890 --> 00:19:26.900
To us it was really a
no-brainer.

00:19:26.900 --> 00:19:30.210
We knew that we would, you know,
increase our sales.

00:19:30.210 --> 00:19:32.960
First year we did 100,000, next
year we did a million, we did

00:19:32.960 --> 00:19:35.460
two million, four million, we
were doubling every year in the

00:19:35.460 --> 00:19:36.460
early days.

00:19:36.460 --> 00:19:37.630
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: It was great for

00:19:37.630 --> 00:19:41.580
the companies-- and even greater
for Jeff Bezos.

00:19:41.580 --> 00:19:44.440
&gt;&gt; Amazon has become the most
recognizable name in e-commerce.

00:19:44.440 --> 00:19:46.960
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Not only would he
take a cut of everything other

00:19:46.960 --> 00:19:51.590
businesses sold, he'd also keep
his own store on the platform,

00:19:51.590 --> 00:19:55.500
competing against everyone else
in the marketplace he owned and

00:19:55.500 --> 00:19:57.020
controlled.

00:19:57.020 --> 00:19:59.090
&gt;&gt; He owns the Main Street.

00:19:59.090 --> 00:20:02.090
He has the Main Street real
estate.

00:20:02.090 --> 00:20:06.720
Not just one building on the
corner, the entire Main Street.

00:20:06.720 --> 00:20:11.201
♪ ♪
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: How Amazon would

00:20:11.201 --> 00:20:14.890
wield its power over the online
marketplace would eventually

00:20:14.890 --> 00:20:19.580
become a question for government
regulators, but early on, there

00:20:19.580 --> 00:20:20.910
were indications.

00:20:20.910 --> 00:20:23.020
The first to see them were book

00:20:23.020 --> 00:20:26.520
publishers.

00:20:26.520 --> 00:20:28.490
&gt;&gt; Amazon took over a large

00:20:28.490 --> 00:20:31.510
market share of the publishing
industry very, very fast.

00:20:31.510 --> 00:20:35.670
They were very quickly in a
position to demand concessions.

00:20:35.670 --> 00:20:37.750
You know, I think that was a
moment where publishers started

00:20:37.750 --> 00:20:40.970
to realize, "Oh, wait a minute,
like, we... they're our partner,

00:20:40.970 --> 00:20:44.380
but they now have the
beginnings of a boot on our

00:20:44.380 --> 00:20:45.380
windpipe."

00:20:45.380 --> 00:20:48.580
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Inside the company,

00:20:48.580 --> 00:20:51.160
they had launched a strategy
that some called "the Gazelle

00:20:51.160 --> 00:20:54.880
Project," because they'd heard
Bezos wanted them to pursue

00:20:54.880 --> 00:20:59.029
publishers the way a cheetah
pursues a sickly gazelle.

00:20:59.029 --> 00:21:00.850
&gt;&gt; Well, you don't go after the
strongest.

00:21:00.850 --> 00:21:01.850
It's like the cheetah.

00:21:01.850 --> 00:21:03.021
The cheetah looks for the weak,

00:21:03.021 --> 00:21:06.900
looks for the sick, looks for
the small, that's what you go

00:21:06.900 --> 00:21:07.900
for.

00:21:07.900 --> 00:21:09.080
So don't start with, you know,

00:21:09.080 --> 00:21:10.360
number one publisher.

00:21:10.360 --> 00:21:11.520
Start with number seven

00:21:11.520 --> 00:21:14.400
publisher and then number six
publisher, and by the time you

00:21:14.400 --> 00:21:18.750
get to number three, two, and
one, the noise has gone, gotten

00:21:18.750 --> 00:21:19.750
back to them.

00:21:19.750 --> 00:21:20.750
They're going to know this is

00:21:20.750 --> 00:21:23.890
coming, and chances are you may
be able to settle that without a

00:21:23.890 --> 00:21:27.930
full-on war.

00:21:27.930 --> 00:21:28.930
&gt;&gt; We were just this little

00:21:28.930 --> 00:21:34.429
mom and pop publishing company,
publishing poetry books and

00:21:34.429 --> 00:21:36.330
translated fiction.

00:21:36.330 --> 00:21:38.559
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: In the early 2000s,

00:21:38.559 --> 00:21:41.780
the number of books Dennis
Johnson was selling on Amazon

00:21:41.780 --> 00:21:43.500
had been rising steadily.

00:21:43.500 --> 00:21:45.620
Then one day, he got a phone

00:21:45.620 --> 00:21:46.650
call.

00:21:46.650 --> 00:21:48.890
&gt;&gt; Our distributor called us up

00:21:48.890 --> 00:21:51.710
to talk about our Amazon
contract.

00:21:51.710 --> 00:21:55.850
And he said, "I went out to
dinner last night with Amazon,

00:21:55.850 --> 00:21:59.640
it was like going out to dinner
with the Godfather.

00:21:59.640 --> 00:22:02.150
They want a kickback."

00:22:02.150 --> 00:22:03.929
That's the word he used,

00:22:03.929 --> 00:22:04.929
kickback.

00:22:04.929 --> 00:22:06.580
And he said they wanted four

00:22:06.580 --> 00:22:10.210
percent more of our sales.

00:22:10.210 --> 00:22:11.210
&gt;&gt; Was that unusual?

00:22:11.210 --> 00:22:16.470
&gt;&gt; It was... in our experience,
it was totally unprecedented,

00:22:16.470 --> 00:22:17.860
yes.

00:22:17.860 --> 00:22:19.890
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Randy Miller ran

00:22:19.890 --> 00:22:23.210
the European book team and says
he saw nothing wrong with

00:22:23.210 --> 00:22:26.810
Amazon's tough tactics to
challenge publishers on prices

00:22:26.810 --> 00:22:28.260
and profit margins.

00:22:28.260 --> 00:22:29.600
&gt;&gt; In order to bring them into

00:22:29.600 --> 00:22:32.450
line, we would actually take
them out of automated

00:22:32.450 --> 00:22:35.890
merchandising, take their prices
up to list price; we would put

00:22:35.890 --> 00:22:39.140
references on the product page,
their product page, saying, "You

00:22:39.140 --> 00:22:42.010
want it cheaper, you want this
book for, on this topic for a

00:22:42.010 --> 00:22:43.010
way cheaper price?

00:22:43.010 --> 00:22:44.010
Click here."

00:22:44.010 --> 00:22:46.049
And we'd send them to whoever we
thought their worst competitor

00:22:46.049 --> 00:22:47.049
was.

00:22:47.049 --> 00:22:49.010
That was how Amazon forced their

00:22:49.010 --> 00:22:51.049
vendors to-to comply.

00:22:51.049 --> 00:22:52.559
(stammering): But that's an

00:22:52.559 --> 00:22:55.790
old Walmart trick, I mean, it
wasn't like Amazon created that.

00:22:55.790 --> 00:22:57.490
And it made, it made a
difference.

00:22:57.490 --> 00:23:01.320
And, you know, Jeff kind of got
excited about it.

00:23:01.320 --> 00:23:04.809
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: When Dennis Johnson
still refused to give in to

00:23:04.809 --> 00:23:08.290
Amazon's terms, he says the buy
button on all Melville House

00:23:08.290 --> 00:23:11.760
books suddenly disappeared,
making it impossible for

00:23:11.760 --> 00:23:14.030
customers to purchase them on
Amazon.

00:23:14.030 --> 00:23:16.610
&gt;&gt; I mean, this is the company
that referred to little

00:23:16.610 --> 00:23:22.420
publishers like me as wounded
gazelles, I believe?

00:23:22.420 --> 00:23:24.220
That's how they think, that's
how he thought from the

00:23:24.220 --> 00:23:25.630
beginning.

00:23:25.630 --> 00:23:28.120
And we eventually had to pay

00:23:28.120 --> 00:23:30.990
what at the time I called a
bribe.

00:23:30.990 --> 00:23:36.960
And our attitude toward Amazon
was, you know, "Render unto

00:23:36.960 --> 00:23:38.320
Caesar that which is Caesar's."

00:23:38.320 --> 00:23:42.210
And then carry on as best as you

00:23:42.210 --> 00:23:43.210
can.

00:23:43.210 --> 00:23:44.210
&gt;&gt; Jeff Bezos may say

00:23:44.210 --> 00:23:48.830
that Amazon comes along and has
given publishers like yourself

00:23:48.830 --> 00:23:53.880
access to a huge distribution
channel for your books.

00:23:53.880 --> 00:23:56.059
Has Amazon been good for your
business?

00:23:56.059 --> 00:23:58.620
&gt;&gt; Well, absolutely they have.

00:23:58.620 --> 00:24:00.049
Any bookseller that sells our

00:24:00.049 --> 00:24:01.950
books is good for our business.

00:24:01.950 --> 00:24:03.720
So, I'm not complaining that

00:24:03.720 --> 00:24:05.350
Amazon is selling our books.

00:24:05.350 --> 00:24:07.260
I'm just complaining of the way

00:24:07.260 --> 00:24:11.149
that their tactics are hurting
the industry I love.

00:24:11.149 --> 00:24:14.480
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: In addition to
granting interviews, Amazon

00:24:14.480 --> 00:24:17.070
responded to written questions.

00:24:17.070 --> 00:24:18.410
Regarding Dennis Johnson's

00:24:18.410 --> 00:24:22.150
characterizations, it told us,
"Amazon disagrees with this

00:24:22.150 --> 00:24:23.150
account."

00:24:23.150 --> 00:24:24.260
&gt;&gt; Were you

00:24:24.260 --> 00:24:27.409
uncomfortable with that sort of
ruthlessness ever?

00:24:27.409 --> 00:24:29.510
&gt;&gt; Well, no, 'cause I was in
retail-- I mean, people think

00:24:29.510 --> 00:24:30.510
that's ruthless.

00:24:30.510 --> 00:24:31.510
You know, I looked, and some

00:24:31.510 --> 00:24:34.450
people at Amazon, "Wow, that's
kind of mean," and I'm like,

00:24:34.450 --> 00:24:36.990
"Oh, a retailer and a supplier
having a disagreement?

00:24:36.990 --> 00:24:38.360
Stop the presses!"

00:24:38.360 --> 00:24:39.410
It happens all the time.

00:24:39.410 --> 00:24:42.330
I mean, you know, look, you've
got a finite margin, and

00:24:42.330 --> 00:24:44.910
somebody's going to have to
give.

00:24:44.910 --> 00:24:47.120
And-and a lot of times Amazon
wasn't the one giving.

00:24:47.120 --> 00:24:50.730
&gt;&gt; Kindle is a purpose-built
reading device.

00:24:50.730 --> 00:24:53.630
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: The tension between
Amazon and book publishers would

00:24:53.630 --> 00:24:57.050
ramp up even further with the
unveiling of the Kindle, which

00:24:57.050 --> 00:25:00.809
helped the industry transition
to the digital age, but gave

00:25:00.809 --> 00:25:03.900
Amazon more power to set prices
lower.

00:25:03.900 --> 00:25:09.470
&gt;&gt; And new releases are only
$9.99.

00:25:09.470 --> 00:25:13.260
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Around that time,
Barry Lynn, an advocate for

00:25:13.260 --> 00:25:17.620
broad antitrust enforcement, was
growing increasingly concerned

00:25:17.620 --> 00:25:19.260
by what he was hearing from
publishers.

00:25:19.260 --> 00:25:23.490
&gt;&gt; If the door was open, the
publisher would say, "Hey, you

00:25:23.490 --> 00:25:26.309
know, Amazon, they're just a
terrific customer, they're our

00:25:26.309 --> 00:25:27.450
biggest customer.

00:25:27.450 --> 00:25:29.560
They buy the most books, they

00:25:29.560 --> 00:25:30.600
sell the most books.

00:25:30.600 --> 00:25:31.679
We love them."

00:25:31.679 --> 00:25:35.530
Then you close the door, and
they say, "Amazon is destroying

00:25:35.530 --> 00:25:38.960
our business model, they're
destroying our business, they

00:25:38.960 --> 00:25:42.950
have way too much power, we
must do something about them."

00:25:42.950 --> 00:25:45.309
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Lynn wanted
publishers to speak up

00:25:45.309 --> 00:25:48.720
publicly and thought federal
antitrust regulators might

00:25:48.720 --> 00:25:53.130
investigate whether Amazon was a
monopoly, illegally abusing its

00:25:53.130 --> 00:25:56.179
market dominance in
anticompetitive ways.

00:25:56.179 --> 00:26:00.549
&gt;&gt; And they'd say, "No way, I'm
not going to talk about Amazon

00:26:00.549 --> 00:26:01.549
in public.

00:26:01.549 --> 00:26:02.549
I'm not talking about them on

00:26:02.549 --> 00:26:03.970
Capitol Hill.

00:26:03.970 --> 00:26:05.470
They will take retribution

00:26:05.470 --> 00:26:06.470
against me."

00:26:06.470 --> 00:26:07.470
&gt;&gt; To which you

00:26:07.470 --> 00:26:08.470
responded?

00:26:08.470 --> 00:26:09.740
&gt;&gt; "Well, that's why we have to

00:26:09.740 --> 00:26:10.830
do something about it."

00:26:10.830 --> 00:26:12.780
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Jennifer Cast ran

00:26:12.780 --> 00:26:16.610
Amazon's books division in its
formative years.

00:26:16.610 --> 00:26:18.700
&gt;&gt; We've had a difficult
time in some ways getting

00:26:18.700 --> 00:26:22.020
publishers to talk to us on
camera about Amazon.

00:26:22.020 --> 00:26:25.790
In part, it seems the reason is
that they're afraid.

00:26:25.790 --> 00:26:30.490
How do you react to that, that
publishers find it

00:26:30.490 --> 00:26:33.210
uncomfortable to talk about
Amazon publicly?

00:26:33.210 --> 00:26:37.460
&gt;&gt; I don't know, I mean, I-I
haven't seen that.

00:26:37.460 --> 00:26:38.460
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:26:38.460 --> 00:26:40.200
&gt;&gt; I haven't been in your shoes.

00:26:40.200 --> 00:26:41.299
I'm sure they have...

00:26:41.299 --> 00:26:43.610
I mean,
if you're saying that they-they

00:26:43.610 --> 00:26:47.020
don't talk negatively about us,
I mean, I know they have a lot

00:26:47.020 --> 00:26:48.740
of good things to say about us.

00:26:48.740 --> 00:26:50.690
Um, you know, I-I don't know why

00:26:50.690 --> 00:26:52.640
they wouldn't speak their minds.

00:26:52.640 --> 00:26:55.100
We certainly value speaking our

00:26:55.100 --> 00:26:56.100
minds.

00:26:56.100 --> 00:26:57.100
&gt;&gt; There is this

00:26:57.100 --> 00:26:59.340
well-known anecdote about
cheetahs and gazelles, this

00:26:59.340 --> 00:27:00.380
Gazelle Program.

00:27:00.380 --> 00:27:01.549
Do you know about that?

00:27:01.549 --> 00:27:03.010
&gt;&gt; I don't.

00:27:03.010 --> 00:27:04.010
&gt;&gt; We've talked to

00:27:04.010 --> 00:27:06.970
former Amazonians about it,
where Jeff had said, "We should

00:27:06.970 --> 00:27:11.660
basically try to negotiate with
book publishers and try to get

00:27:11.660 --> 00:27:15.130
better terms and treat the
smaller publishers as a cheetah

00:27:15.130 --> 00:27:17.000
would go after a wounded
gazelle."

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:21.169
&gt;&gt; I didn't hear the cheetah
and gazelle example, but what we

00:27:21.169 --> 00:27:24.980
were looking for was people that
were willing to move away from

00:27:24.980 --> 00:27:28.610
the old model of bricks and
mortar to a new model, which

00:27:28.610 --> 00:27:35.120
was, you know, a-a virtual store
that had many different types of

00:27:35.120 --> 00:27:38.460
opportunities to present their
books to customers.

00:27:38.460 --> 00:27:41.980
&gt;&gt; I want to talk a little bit
about how we think about

00:27:41.980 --> 00:27:43.679
innovation at Amazon.com.

00:27:43.679 --> 00:27:45.110
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Amazon would begin

00:27:45.110 --> 00:27:50.170
to accumulate even more power in
2005, when Bezos quietly rolled

00:27:50.170 --> 00:27:53.730
out a revolutionary new program:
Amazon Prime.

00:27:53.730 --> 00:27:55.309
&gt;&gt; Now they have something
called the Prime shipping

00:27:55.309 --> 00:27:57.240
program.

00:27:57.240 --> 00:27:58.380
&gt;&gt; Amazon Prime-- we only

00:27:58.380 --> 00:28:03.440
launched this a week ago--
you pay $79 a year, and you get

00:28:03.440 --> 00:28:05.009
two-day shipping for free.

00:28:05.009 --> 00:28:07.180
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: It was a risky bet,

00:28:07.180 --> 00:28:08.370
and it paid off.

00:28:08.370 --> 00:28:09.710
&gt;&gt; The lynchpin, or the glue, if

00:28:09.710 --> 00:28:13.290
you will, and probably the
seminal moment in Amazon's

00:28:13.290 --> 00:28:17.690
business history, was the
introduction of what has become

00:28:17.690 --> 00:28:21.809
the most successful membership
program in history, and that's

00:28:21.809 --> 00:28:22.809
Prime.

00:28:22.809 --> 00:28:23.809
&gt;&gt; Many of you in this audience

00:28:23.809 --> 00:28:27.049
will already be Amazon Prime
members, bless you.

00:28:27.049 --> 00:28:28.400
This is very much appreciated.

00:28:28.400 --> 00:28:30.790
&gt;&gt; It changes the way you shop.

00:28:30.790 --> 00:28:33.799
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Eventually more
than 150 million people would

00:28:33.799 --> 00:28:38.110
sign up for the free shipping--
a tremendous expense for Amazon.

00:28:38.110 --> 00:28:41.610
But to Bezos, it was worth it.

00:28:41.610 --> 00:28:43.200
&gt;&gt; The Prime program at Amazon

00:28:43.200 --> 00:28:47.440
is one of the most important
drivers of Amazon's growth.

00:28:47.440 --> 00:28:50.309
When you go on and look to buy a
product, and it's available in

00:28:50.309 --> 00:28:54.350
two days, delivered to your door
anywhere in the country, that

00:28:54.350 --> 00:28:58.090
Amazon Prime program becomes a
mechanism that keeps bringing

00:28:58.090 --> 00:29:00.910
you back as a customer to keep
buying and keep searching for

00:29:00.910 --> 00:29:03.299
new products on Amazon.

00:29:03.299 --> 00:29:05.510
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Two-day delivery

00:29:05.510 --> 00:29:08.750
anywhere in the country was a
big promise for a company that,

00:29:08.750 --> 00:29:12.030
at the time, had less than ten
warehouses.

00:29:12.030 --> 00:29:18.210
So Bezos went on a building
spree.

00:29:18.210 --> 00:29:19.679
♪ ♪
Across the country Amazon

00:29:19.679 --> 00:29:24.220
warehouses began to spring up,
filled with millions of

00:29:24.220 --> 00:29:27.360
products being sold on Bezos's
platform.

00:29:27.360 --> 00:29:31.850
He'd call them fulfillment
centers, and they'd create

00:29:31.850 --> 00:29:35.309
hundreds of thousands of jobs
in places hard hit by the Great

00:29:35.309 --> 00:29:36.960
Recession.

00:29:36.960 --> 00:29:40.370
&gt;&gt; Ten percent of Pennsylvania

00:29:40.370 --> 00:29:41.370
residents unemployed...

00:29:41.370 --> 00:29:42.370
&gt;&gt; Job market is in complete

00:29:42.370 --> 00:29:43.370
disarray.

00:29:43.370 --> 00:29:44.370
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Like Allentown,

00:29:44.370 --> 00:29:45.370
Pennsylvania.

00:29:45.370 --> 00:29:46.370
&gt;&gt; At that time, it was

00:29:46.370 --> 00:29:48.600
tremendous news that an employer
was coming and actually opening

00:29:48.600 --> 00:29:53.900
a facility and hiring people,
versus, you know, gutting half

00:29:53.900 --> 00:29:54.900
the staff.

00:29:54.900 --> 00:29:55.900
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Spencer Soper was a

00:29:55.900 --> 00:29:57.850
business reporter for the
"Allentown Morning Call" when

00:29:57.850 --> 00:30:00.500
Amazon opened in the area in
2010.

00:30:00.500 --> 00:30:07.210
He began hearing stories about
working in the warehouse.

00:30:07.210 --> 00:30:10.870
&gt;&gt; People are basically in this
big, sprawling warehouse that's

00:30:10.870 --> 00:30:13.880
stocked with goods in very
random fashion.

00:30:13.880 --> 00:30:17.600
And they have scanners that
tell them which things to get.

00:30:17.600 --> 00:30:19.820
And people are walking maybe
ten, 15 miles a day.

00:30:19.820 --> 00:30:22.190
So people just kind of
crisscrossing this big warehouse

00:30:22.190 --> 00:30:23.570
all day long.

00:30:23.570 --> 00:30:25.120
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: As workers told him

00:30:25.120 --> 00:30:27.919
about the punishing pace to meet
the daily quota of packages, and

00:30:27.919 --> 00:30:32.640
the intense heat, Soper and his
colleagues started to

00:30:32.640 --> 00:30:34.609
investigate further.

00:30:34.609 --> 00:30:35.609
&gt;&gt; People really felt like

00:30:35.609 --> 00:30:38.410
Amazon was playing fast and
loose with their, with their

00:30:38.410 --> 00:30:39.410
health.

00:30:39.410 --> 00:30:40.679
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Soper discovered

00:30:40.679 --> 00:30:43.070
there had been numerous
complaints to authorities at the

00:30:43.070 --> 00:30:46.510
Occupational Safety and Health
Administration, OSHA.

00:30:46.510 --> 00:30:50.230
&gt;&gt; They actually had a complaint
from an emergency-room doctor

00:30:50.230 --> 00:30:55.159
who called their hotline one day
saying, "Listen, you might want

00:30:55.159 --> 00:30:56.720
to check out this Amazon place.

00:30:56.720 --> 00:30:57.970
I've had, like, people parading

00:30:57.970 --> 00:31:01.480
through my emergency room to be
treated for heat stress."

00:31:01.480 --> 00:31:04.570
There was a security guard who
worked in the facility who sent

00:31:04.570 --> 00:31:08.179
a complaint to OSHA saying that
he saw pregnant women suffering

00:31:08.179 --> 00:31:11.179
heat stress in-in the facility.

00:31:11.179 --> 00:31:12.179
And so there's just, like, these

00:31:12.179 --> 00:31:14.850
red flags right and left.

00:31:14.850 --> 00:31:16.610
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: After an

00:31:16.610 --> 00:31:19.600
investigation, OSHA said Amazon
needed to keep the temperatures

00:31:19.600 --> 00:31:21.220
in the warehouses lower.

00:31:21.220 --> 00:31:23.330
In a statement at the time, the

00:31:23.330 --> 00:31:26.660
company said it installed new
industrial air conditioning and

00:31:26.660 --> 00:31:31.070
pledged that worker safety was
its number-one priority.

00:31:31.070 --> 00:31:32.340
&gt;&gt; Amazon is shrewd
businesspeople, shrewd

00:31:32.340 --> 00:31:34.660
businesspeople know when they
have leverage.

00:31:34.660 --> 00:31:38.170
And when you're the only shop
hiring people in town, you can

00:31:38.170 --> 00:31:42.429
push them a lot harder than
you can when-when they've got

00:31:42.429 --> 00:31:43.429
alternatives.

00:31:43.429 --> 00:31:45.020
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Over the following

00:31:45.020 --> 00:31:47.490
years, Amazon would hire
hundreds of thousands of

00:31:47.490 --> 00:31:49.710
workers and become one of
the largest jobs

00:31:49.710 --> 00:31:52.440
creators in the country.

00:31:52.440 --> 00:31:54.240
At the fulfillment centers,

00:31:54.240 --> 00:31:57.779
Bezos experimented with new
techniques and technologies to

00:31:57.779 --> 00:31:59.820
boost productivity.

00:31:59.820 --> 00:32:01.110
&gt;&gt; Willingness to experiment is

00:32:01.110 --> 00:32:03.230
the key to be able to do new
things.

00:32:03.230 --> 00:32:07.020
So we do, you know, hundreds of
experiments every day in our

00:32:07.020 --> 00:32:09.420
fulfillment centers to get a
little bit better.

00:32:09.420 --> 00:32:11.669
Kind of like incremental
invention.

00:32:11.669 --> 00:32:15.320
♪ ♪
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: When a company

00:32:15.320 --> 00:32:19.080
called Kiva perfected a
warehouse robot, Amazon bought

00:32:19.080 --> 00:32:20.080
the whole company.

00:32:20.080 --> 00:32:21.760
&gt;&gt; Amazon has acquired Kiva

00:32:21.760 --> 00:32:22.760
Systems.

00:32:22.760 --> 00:32:24.110
They make shipping robots.

00:32:24.110 --> 00:32:27.740
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: It helped transform
the work environment in Amazon's

00:32:27.740 --> 00:32:32.250
warehouses.

00:32:32.250 --> 00:32:33.281
&gt;&gt; When I first showed up at

00:32:33.281 --> 00:32:36.370
Amazon in 1999, I led our Global
Operations team.

00:32:36.370 --> 00:32:39.610
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Jeff Wilke created
the Amazon fulfillment center

00:32:39.610 --> 00:32:44.530
system and is one of two C.E.O.s
under Jeff Bezos.

00:32:44.530 --> 00:32:47.799
&gt;&gt; As we've added 200,000
robots, in that same time frame

00:32:47.799 --> 00:32:51.500
since 2012 we've added 300,000
people in our fulfillment

00:32:51.500 --> 00:32:52.500
centers.

00:32:52.500 --> 00:32:53.500
So what happens is the robots

00:32:53.500 --> 00:32:55.669
change the work, so they allow
us... people don't have to walk

00:32:55.669 --> 00:32:58.289
as far, which is a complaint
that we've heard in the past.

00:32:58.289 --> 00:33:01.190
They make the job safer, they
make them higher quality,

00:33:01.190 --> 00:33:05.890
because we present a smaller set
of options to-to employees.

00:33:05.890 --> 00:33:07.700
And that's all good for
customers, and it's good for

00:33:07.700 --> 00:33:08.700
employees too.

00:33:08.700 --> 00:33:10.051
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: But at the same

00:33:10.051 --> 00:33:13.400
time, complaints have persisted.

00:33:13.400 --> 00:33:14.400
&gt;&gt; People who've worked in

00:33:14.400 --> 00:33:16.540
warehouses for decades say,
"This is different.

00:33:16.540 --> 00:33:19.029
This is not the same."

00:33:19.029 --> 00:33:20.039
We're here today because we

00:33:20.039 --> 00:33:22.370
want to make sure that these
workers know about their rights

00:33:22.370 --> 00:33:24.559
in the workplace, especially
around heat.

00:33:24.559 --> 00:33:27.220
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Sheheryar Kaoosji
is an advocate for warehouse

00:33:27.220 --> 00:33:31.230
workers in the San Bernardino,
California, area-- an Amazon

00:33:31.230 --> 00:33:35.630
hub, with ten fulfillment
centers and over 15,000

00:33:35.630 --> 00:33:37.090
employees.

00:33:37.090 --> 00:33:38.110
&gt;&gt; Because of the way that

00:33:38.110 --> 00:33:41.360
Amazon operates, because of the
way that they set their rates

00:33:41.360 --> 00:33:46.150
for productivity, it's a lot
harder work physically but also

00:33:46.150 --> 00:33:47.150
psychologically.

00:33:47.150 --> 00:33:48.940
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: We sat down with a

00:33:48.940 --> 00:33:53.450
group in San Bernardino who'd
recently worked at Amazon.

00:33:53.450 --> 00:33:55.160
&gt;&gt; When they first got here, I
thought it was exciting.

00:33:55.160 --> 00:33:58.890
Like, for me, I was thinking
maybe I could find a-a place

00:33:58.890 --> 00:34:01.520
where, you know, I'm going to
set roots of a good job, you

00:34:01.520 --> 00:34:03.110
know, move up in-in the place.

00:34:03.110 --> 00:34:04.659
But after being there for a

00:34:04.659 --> 00:34:07.019
while, I was like, "There's no
way."

00:34:07.019 --> 00:34:09.179
&gt;&gt; It's like, "Okay, this is
where I can probably make a

00:34:09.179 --> 00:34:10.179
career."

00:34:10.179 --> 00:34:12.010
But once you worked there for a

00:34:12.010 --> 00:34:14.980
certain amount of time, it's
just like, it's just not

00:34:14.980 --> 00:34:17.290
realistic, how they expect you
to work.

00:34:17.290 --> 00:34:20.040
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Like dozens of
workers we've spoken to around

00:34:20.040 --> 00:34:23.320
the country, they say they've
struggled to keep up with the

00:34:23.320 --> 00:34:27.619
rate Amazon expected them to
pick and pack items.

00:34:27.619 --> 00:34:30.440
&gt;&gt; How realistic are the
rates that they're giving you?

00:34:30.440 --> 00:34:32.440
I mean, what's...

00:34:32.440 --> 00:34:33.440
&gt;&gt; Not realistic at all.

00:34:33.440 --> 00:34:34.440
&gt;&gt; Not-not realistic?

00:34:34.440 --> 00:34:35.440
&gt;&gt; No.

00:34:35.440 --> 00:34:36.609
There's absolutely no way to
make rate, you know, you got to

00:34:36.609 --> 00:34:39.800
find little ways to-to cheat
it, because once you hit rate,

00:34:39.800 --> 00:34:42.570
by the end of the week, they
raised it, they bump it up

00:34:42.570 --> 00:34:43.720
again.

00:34:43.720 --> 00:34:45.000
Because they start seeing, "Hey,

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:47.320
people can hit those rates,
can hit those numbers, hey,

00:34:47.320 --> 00:34:50.430
let's push them a little
harder."

00:34:50.430 --> 00:34:58.890
Every week it seemed like it was
going up.

00:34:58.890 --> 00:35:00.440
♪ ♪
&gt;&gt; You have security cameras

00:35:00.440 --> 00:35:03.170
right behind you at all times,
that are looking at you

00:35:03.170 --> 00:35:04.170
24-seven.

00:35:04.170 --> 00:35:07.020
And if you don't meet standards

00:35:07.020 --> 00:35:11.970
or the rates, you're out the
door, you're just disposable.

00:35:11.970 --> 00:35:15.100
&gt;&gt; Every worker has a scanner at
all times that basically track

00:35:15.100 --> 00:35:17.370
exactly where you're at.

00:35:17.370 --> 00:35:19.161
&gt;&gt; And they have a little blue

00:35:19.161 --> 00:35:23.801
line at the bottom of the
screen, and it has, like, how

00:35:23.801 --> 00:35:29.300
many seconds that you have to
have it done by the time it hits

00:35:29.300 --> 00:35:31.810
zero, and it puts you into panic
mode.

00:35:31.810 --> 00:35:35.170
&gt;&gt; And pretty much you can't
talk to people, you can't be in

00:35:35.170 --> 00:35:37.802
the same aisle as them, you
just constantly have to sit

00:35:37.802 --> 00:35:40.530
there scanning like a robot all
day long.

00:35:40.530 --> 00:35:43.040
If they catch you not scanning,
you get a write-up.

00:35:43.040 --> 00:35:45.800
&gt;&gt; And what they're doing is
they're producing this mass of

00:35:45.800 --> 00:35:49.810
data that they are using to be
able to analyze the entire

00:35:49.810 --> 00:35:53.190
workforce.

00:35:53.190 --> 00:35:54.480
&gt;&gt; We're not treated as human

00:35:54.480 --> 00:35:57.020
beings, we're not even treated
as robots.

00:35:57.020 --> 00:36:00.400
We're treated as part of the
data stream.

00:36:00.400 --> 00:36:03.570
&gt;&gt; It's the incentive at
any warehouse, on any assembly

00:36:03.570 --> 00:36:05.630
line, to get the most out of any
worker.

00:36:05.630 --> 00:36:06.630
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:36:06.630 --> 00:36:07.710
&gt;&gt; To make rates, to-to

00:36:07.710 --> 00:36:10.349
be as efficient as possible, to
be as productive as possible.

00:36:10.349 --> 00:36:13.920
So, I don't see exactly what's
different about Amazon as

00:36:13.920 --> 00:36:16.710
opposed to any other warehouse.

00:36:16.710 --> 00:36:20.020
&gt;&gt; Amazon is the cutting edge.

00:36:20.020 --> 00:36:22.839
Other warehouses are starting to
adopt these technologies, other

00:36:22.839 --> 00:36:25.599
companies are definitely
interested in doing what Amazon

00:36:25.599 --> 00:36:26.850
is doing.

00:36:26.850 --> 00:36:27.900
Data collection could become

00:36:27.900 --> 00:36:31.200
basically the standard for all
workers, and that there's...

00:36:31.200 --> 00:36:36.870
you're never good enough,
you're never able to keep up.

00:36:36.870 --> 00:36:39.410
♪ ♪
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Amazon told us work

00:36:39.410 --> 00:36:42.330
rates are not based on
individual employee's

00:36:42.330 --> 00:36:45.560
performance, and that the
scanning devices workers use are

00:36:45.560 --> 00:36:49.619
not for tracking people but
inventory-- a common practice in

00:36:49.619 --> 00:36:52.660
the warehouse industry.

00:36:52.660 --> 00:36:53.660
&gt;&gt; We've talked to

00:36:53.660 --> 00:36:56.960
workers around the country,
both current and former workers.

00:36:56.960 --> 00:37:01.150
They've described the pace of
work as being really grueling.

00:37:01.150 --> 00:37:04.310
In the early thinking about
rates and how far you could

00:37:04.310 --> 00:37:07.910
push human beings in terms of
their productivity, what was the

00:37:07.910 --> 00:37:09.330
thinking about that?

00:37:09.330 --> 00:37:11.130
&gt;&gt; Well, obviously if the rates

00:37:11.130 --> 00:37:13.470
are too high, you're not going
to have people showing up for

00:37:13.470 --> 00:37:14.470
work.

00:37:14.470 --> 00:37:16.881
So, we have 600,000 people at

00:37:16.881 --> 00:37:19.890
the company, most of them are in
the fulfillment centers, and

00:37:19.890 --> 00:37:24.580
they-they come to work every
day, they stay for years.

00:37:24.580 --> 00:37:27.460
These are considered great jobs
in the hundreds of communities

00:37:27.460 --> 00:37:29.320
where we have fulfillment
centers all over the world,

00:37:29.320 --> 00:37:33.140
and in the U.S. we have, almost
every state has an operation in

00:37:33.140 --> 00:37:35.830
it, and people come to work
because these are great jobs.

00:37:35.830 --> 00:37:38.480
They're safe, we pay double the
minimum wage, the national

00:37:38.480 --> 00:37:40.810
minimum wage, we have terrific
benefits.

00:37:40.810 --> 00:37:43.021
The benefits for the folks that
work on the floor are the same

00:37:43.021 --> 00:37:45.950
benefits that my family has
access to-- our family leave is

00:37:45.950 --> 00:37:47.710
like 20 weeks.

00:37:47.710 --> 00:37:50.710
So, the rates are set so that we

00:37:50.710 --> 00:37:53.430
can accomplish what we need to,
which is get orders to customers

00:37:53.430 --> 00:37:57.420
in a-a reasonable time and in a
high-quality way, and that

00:37:57.420 --> 00:38:01.800
creates a workplace that people
want to come back to, and they

00:38:01.800 --> 00:38:02.800
do.

00:38:02.800 --> 00:38:03.820
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Amazon wouldn't

00:38:03.820 --> 00:38:06.280
tell us how long
fulfillment-center workers stay

00:38:06.280 --> 00:38:09.780
on the job or how often they're
injured.

00:38:09.780 --> 00:38:12.420
But workers we spoke to say the
rates are higher than other

00:38:12.420 --> 00:38:16.180
warehouses-- and that the
company rebuffs attempts to

00:38:16.180 --> 00:38:18.710
unionize.

00:38:18.710 --> 00:38:19.930
&gt;&gt; We do not believe unions are

00:38:19.930 --> 00:38:22.890
in the best interest of our
customers, our shareholders, or

00:38:22.890 --> 00:38:24.840
most importantly, our
associates.

00:38:24.840 --> 00:38:27.540
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: This is a clip from
a video the company says it

00:38:27.540 --> 00:38:30.680
used in the past to teach
managers about employees'

00:38:30.680 --> 00:38:32.660
rights and labor laws.

00:38:32.660 --> 00:38:34.050
&gt;&gt; The most obvious signs would

00:38:34.050 --> 00:38:37.890
include use of words associated
with unions or union-led

00:38:37.890 --> 00:38:41.160
movements like "living wage" or
"steward."

00:38:41.160 --> 00:38:44.350
&gt;&gt; Early on, Amazon took
a position to basically be

00:38:44.350 --> 00:38:45.920
anti-union.

00:38:45.920 --> 00:38:47.140
Why was that decision made?

00:38:47.140 --> 00:38:49.609
&gt;&gt; I don't think we made the
decision to be anti-union.

00:38:49.609 --> 00:38:52.990
We just feel that all of the
things that-that unions

00:38:52.990 --> 00:38:57.779
would-would want to-to get us
to do, we've already done.

00:38:57.779 --> 00:38:59.609
&gt;&gt; What-what about
setting rate, though?

00:38:59.609 --> 00:39:02.170
Do you not see that there's a
little bit more leverage in the

00:39:02.170 --> 00:39:05.090
hands of management in this
scenario than there would be in

00:39:05.090 --> 00:39:06.090
a unionized environment?

00:39:06.090 --> 00:39:07.510
&gt;&gt; I don't know, it's hard to

00:39:07.510 --> 00:39:10.420
speculate on that, but-but I do
think that we have the

00:39:10.420 --> 00:39:14.400
obligation to set rates that
are, again, going to encourage

00:39:14.400 --> 00:39:20.280
people to seek these jobs and
deliver for customers, you know,

00:39:20.280 --> 00:39:21.280
what we've promised.

00:39:21.280 --> 00:39:22.280
&gt;&gt; What would you say to

00:39:22.280 --> 00:39:24.790
someone, though, who's, who's
worked in-in your fulfillment

00:39:24.790 --> 00:39:28.670
centers that feels as though
there's been... that-that humans

00:39:28.670 --> 00:39:31.660
are increasingly being treated
like robots?

00:39:31.660 --> 00:39:33.560
'Cause it's something that we've
actually heard, and I don't

00:39:33.560 --> 00:39:35.540
sense it's hyperbole.

00:39:35.540 --> 00:39:37.310
&gt;&gt; Well, that's not the

00:39:37.310 --> 00:39:40.800
experience that-that I had in
setting it up or that I've

00:39:40.800 --> 00:39:41.800
seen.

00:39:41.800 --> 00:39:43.210
It's, it's certainly true

00:39:43.210 --> 00:39:46.921
that-that these jobs are not for
everybody, and there-there may

00:39:46.921 --> 00:39:50.010
be people that don't want to do
this kind of work.

00:39:50.010 --> 00:39:52.820
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Amazon executives
also stress the company has

00:39:52.820 --> 00:39:55.960
become an industry leader in
training its workforce for

00:39:55.960 --> 00:39:58.290
career advancement.

00:39:58.290 --> 00:39:59.530
&gt;&gt; We just announced a pledge

00:39:59.530 --> 00:40:04.089
recently to spend $700 million
to upskill, which is basically

00:40:04.089 --> 00:40:07.191
creating career opportunities
for people, 100,000 of our

00:40:07.191 --> 00:40:08.191
employees.

00:40:08.191 --> 00:40:09.650
We pay 95% of tuition to go

00:40:09.650 --> 00:40:13.599
to-to college to get a skill
that isn't about Amazon, that's

00:40:13.599 --> 00:40:16.440
about creating options for the
employees, and I would expect

00:40:16.440 --> 00:40:19.540
those people to take advantage
of that, work for us for a

00:40:19.540 --> 00:40:22.000
couple of years and then go do
something that they would much

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:25.099
rather do, and that's okay.

00:40:25.099 --> 00:40:27.080
&gt;&gt; There will be people

00:40:27.080 --> 00:40:30.900
that will hear what y'all are
saying, and they'll say, "Well,

00:40:30.900 --> 00:40:34.510
you signed up for physical
labor, a job is a job, there

00:40:34.510 --> 00:40:39.609
were benefits, and they are now
investing $700 million to

00:40:39.609 --> 00:40:42.690
do retraining for other types of
jobs.

00:40:42.690 --> 00:40:43.740
What's the real grievance?

00:40:43.740 --> 00:40:44.760
What is there to complain

00:40:44.760 --> 00:40:45.760
about?"

00:40:45.760 --> 00:40:46.760
&gt;&gt; I actually used to think that

00:40:46.760 --> 00:40:49.760
way for a while whenever I, when
I first started, whoever I heard

00:40:49.760 --> 00:40:51.609
complaints from, I was like,
"Well, it was in the job

00:40:51.609 --> 00:40:53.820
description, and you signed up
for it."

00:40:53.820 --> 00:41:00.000
The part they don't talk about
is the safety rules that you

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:02.130
have to ignore to make rate.

00:41:02.130 --> 00:41:03.130
It's not just you go in, okay,

00:41:03.130 --> 00:41:05.550
and you-you do your job, and
that's it.

00:41:05.550 --> 00:41:07.980
&gt;&gt; So, you're in, you're
in a weird bind.

00:41:07.980 --> 00:41:12.849
&gt;&gt; It's incredibly hard to meet
rate while following all the

00:41:12.849 --> 00:41:15.770
safety procedures.

00:41:15.770 --> 00:41:16.770
&gt;&gt; A complaint that

00:41:16.770 --> 00:41:19.710
we've heard from workers in
terms of the sort of automation

00:41:19.710 --> 00:41:23.241
of their work as humans, some of
them telling us that, yes, there

00:41:23.241 --> 00:41:26.430
are high safety standards in
these fulfillment centers, but

00:41:26.430 --> 00:41:29.140
that in order to make rate,
they're having to cheat the

00:41:29.140 --> 00:41:30.140
standard a little bit.

00:41:30.140 --> 00:41:31.140
&gt;&gt; Well, I would say that's not

00:41:31.140 --> 00:41:32.140
okay.

00:41:32.140 --> 00:41:34.079
So I, from the moment that I

00:41:34.079 --> 00:41:37.619
arrived 20 years ago, I made it
very clear to our operations

00:41:37.619 --> 00:41:40.240
teams that we will not
compromise the safety of our

00:41:40.240 --> 00:41:42.780
employees to do anything else.

00:41:42.780 --> 00:41:44.440
So, we have, we have a culture

00:41:44.440 --> 00:41:48.780
that if-if we are asking people
to do something that is, that

00:41:48.780 --> 00:41:52.000
they have to do too fast to be
safe, they can raise their hand

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:54.600
and say, "This isn't right,"
and-and we'll fix it.

00:41:54.600 --> 00:41:58.040
(phone vibrates)
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: For years, Amazon

00:41:58.040 --> 00:42:00.980
has put a happy face on its
business and its workforce.

00:42:00.980 --> 00:42:04.830
("Give a Little Bit" by
Supertramp playing)

00:42:04.830 --> 00:42:10.320
&gt;&gt; ♪ Give a little bit
Give a little bit of your

00:42:10.320 --> 00:42:11.320
love...

00:42:11.320 --> 00:42:12.670
♪
&gt;&gt; Even in Amazon's commercials,

00:42:12.670 --> 00:42:16.320
the people are almost like
shadows and silhouettes.

00:42:16.320 --> 00:42:18.490
It's all about boxes, and
there's just like happy boxes

00:42:18.490 --> 00:42:21.920
singing and bumbling their way
to your door, like, oh, no, no.

00:42:21.920 --> 00:42:24.319
&gt;&gt; ♪ There's so much that we
need.

00:42:24.319 --> 00:42:25.319
♪

00:42:25.319 --> 00:42:26.319
&gt;&gt; Hello.

00:42:26.319 --> 00:42:27.319
&gt;&gt; Hey.

00:42:27.319 --> 00:42:28.319
&gt;&gt; They don't want you to even
think about how they do this.

00:42:28.319 --> 00:42:31.150
They just want you to be wowed
and, "Oh, how'd this, how'd this

00:42:31.150 --> 00:42:32.150
get here?"

00:42:32.150 --> 00:42:34.960
&gt;&gt; ♪ I'll give a little bit of

00:42:34.960 --> 00:42:36.900
my love to you.

00:42:36.900 --> 00:42:37.900
♪
&gt;&gt; They wanted people to just

00:42:37.900 --> 00:42:41.960
think, "Whoa, magic!"

00:42:41.960 --> 00:42:42.960
♪ ♪

00:42:42.960 --> 00:42:47.280
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: And magic was a big
part of Bezos' marketing

00:42:47.280 --> 00:42:51.070
strategy, with an emphasis on
the company's miraculous level

00:42:51.070 --> 00:42:54.640
of innovation and growth.

00:42:54.640 --> 00:42:56.980
&gt;&gt; We started Amazon Prime in

00:42:56.980 --> 00:43:03.060
2005, but then something very
extraordinary happened.

00:43:03.060 --> 00:43:04.640
This.

00:43:04.640 --> 00:43:09.260
In 2011, the slope of that graph

00:43:09.260 --> 00:43:11.030
changed-- a lot.

00:43:11.030 --> 00:43:13.820
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: As Amazon grew, he

00:43:13.820 --> 00:43:16.609
wanted his top executives to
think about the kind of company

00:43:16.609 --> 00:43:18.230
it was becoming.

00:43:18.230 --> 00:43:22.930
He wrote a memo titled,

00:43:22.930 --> 00:43:23.930
"Amazon.love."

00:43:23.930 --> 00:43:26.030
A copy of it was obtained by

00:43:26.030 --> 00:43:28.130
Brad Stone.

00:43:28.130 --> 00:43:29.780
&gt;&gt; The memo is another example

00:43:29.780 --> 00:43:32.880
of Jeff being very prescient
about the future.

00:43:32.880 --> 00:43:35.730
It's Jeff grappling with the
idea that not all big companies

00:43:35.730 --> 00:43:36.770
are loved.

00:43:36.770 --> 00:43:38.329
That there is something that we

00:43:38.329 --> 00:43:42.530
get uncomfortable with when we
talk about very big companies.

00:43:42.530 --> 00:43:45.840
"Rudeness is not cool.

00:43:45.840 --> 00:43:48.540
Defeating tiny guys is not cool.

00:43:48.540 --> 00:43:50.200
Risk taking is cool.

00:43:50.200 --> 00:43:51.200
Winning is cool.

00:43:51.200 --> 00:43:52.710
Polite is cool.

00:43:52.710 --> 00:43:54.349
Defeating bigger, unsympathetic

00:43:54.349 --> 00:43:56.530
guys is cool.

00:43:56.530 --> 00:43:57.869
Inventing is cool.

00:43:57.869 --> 00:43:59.910
Explorers are cool.

00:43:59.910 --> 00:44:03.320
Conquerors are not cool."

00:44:03.320 --> 00:44:05.170
&gt;&gt; Some businesses, you can
tell when you go in and have

00:44:05.170 --> 00:44:09.349
meetings with them, they have a
conqueror mentality.

00:44:09.349 --> 00:44:11.540
And there's a big difference
between being a conqueror and

00:44:11.540 --> 00:44:13.310
being an explorer.

00:44:13.310 --> 00:44:14.550
And I think in, you know, this

00:44:14.550 --> 00:44:21.380
very inventive space that we're
in, it pays to explore.

00:44:21.380 --> 00:44:24.481
♪ ♪
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: But to some

00:44:24.481 --> 00:44:27.930
watching Amazon's growth, the
company was falling short of

00:44:27.930 --> 00:44:32.050
that ideal, and taking steps to
make sure nothing got in its

00:44:32.050 --> 00:44:36.020
way.

00:44:36.020 --> 00:44:37.020
♪ ♪

00:44:37.020 --> 00:44:40.710
In 2013, Amazon was moving to
create its own delivery system

00:44:40.710 --> 00:44:45.510
and made a key decision: rather
than hire its own drivers, it

00:44:45.510 --> 00:44:50.870
built a network of independent
businesses to deliver packages.

00:44:50.870 --> 00:44:53.720
&gt;&gt; They weren't just going to
dabble here and dabble there.

00:44:53.720 --> 00:44:57.849
They were going to go and create
a system that would rival

00:44:57.849 --> 00:45:00.240
FedEx or UPS.

00:45:00.240 --> 00:45:02.520
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: ProPublica reporter

00:45:02.520 --> 00:45:06.500
Patricia Callahan, in
conjunction with Buzzfeed, has

00:45:06.500 --> 00:45:09.630
investigated the system Amazon
set up.

00:45:09.630 --> 00:45:13.080
&gt;&gt; They figured out a way to get
around regulation.

00:45:13.080 --> 00:45:16.400
The cargo vans they choose are
big enough to stuff with

00:45:16.400 --> 00:45:20.330
hundreds of Amazon packages, but
they're small enough that

00:45:20.330 --> 00:45:22.350
they're not regulated by the
federal government.

00:45:22.350 --> 00:45:25.230
&gt;&gt; An 84-year-old woman struck
and killed by an Amazon

00:45:25.230 --> 00:45:26.300
delivery truck.

00:45:26.300 --> 00:45:28.109
&gt;&gt; A woman hit and killed in a

00:45:28.109 --> 00:45:29.109
parking lot.

00:45:29.109 --> 00:45:30.109
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: ProPublica and

00:45:30.109 --> 00:45:33.000
Buzzfeed found that drivers are
under intense pressure to

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:34.520
deliver packages.

00:45:34.520 --> 00:45:35.520
&gt;&gt; After striking him, the

00:45:35.520 --> 00:45:37.740
van maneuvered around Salinas
and his dog.

00:45:37.740 --> 00:45:40.860
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: And they documented
more than 60 crashes, including

00:45:40.860 --> 00:45:43.470
13 deaths, since 2015.

00:45:43.470 --> 00:45:45.270
&gt;&gt; An infant critically injured

00:45:45.270 --> 00:45:47.339
in a car crash has died.

00:45:47.339 --> 00:45:49.010
&gt;&gt; When it came time to figure

00:45:49.010 --> 00:45:53.160
out who's responsible, Amazon
would always say, "It's a

00:45:53.160 --> 00:45:54.770
contractor, it's not our
responsibility."

00:45:54.770 --> 00:45:58.750
&gt;&gt; Now you've been able
to find 13 deaths.

00:45:58.750 --> 00:46:01.100
And that's over the course of
several years.

00:46:01.100 --> 00:46:04.380
Is that statistically
significant given all of the

00:46:04.380 --> 00:46:07.829
packages that they deliver in
any day or any given year?

00:46:07.829 --> 00:46:11.630
&gt;&gt; I don't pretend to claim
that there's only 13 deaths and

00:46:11.630 --> 00:46:13.859
that I found every single one.

00:46:13.859 --> 00:46:16.980
I just found enough to show that

00:46:16.980 --> 00:46:19.980
this is happening around the
country.

00:46:19.980 --> 00:46:22.690
With UPS, there's a record.

00:46:22.690 --> 00:46:24.010
There's a federal record you can

00:46:24.010 --> 00:46:27.420
look at how many serious injury
and fatal accidents they have.

00:46:27.420 --> 00:46:30.250
With Amazon, that doesn't exist.

00:46:30.250 --> 00:46:32.140
No one knows the safety records

00:46:32.140 --> 00:46:36.150
of all of Amazon’s contractors.

00:46:36.150 --> 00:46:38.330
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Amazon disputed the

00:46:38.330 --> 00:46:40.609
ProPublica report.

00:46:40.609 --> 00:46:42.210
It would not release any data on

00:46:42.210 --> 00:46:45.990
crashes involving its driver
network but told us it had a

00:46:45.990 --> 00:46:49.580
"better than average" safety
record and that nothing is more

00:46:49.580 --> 00:46:53.840
important to them than safety.

00:46:53.840 --> 00:46:55.820
&gt;&gt; Any accident is one accident

00:46:55.820 --> 00:46:58.730
too many, so just as we were
focused on safety in the

00:46:58.730 --> 00:47:02.330
fulfillment centers and product
safety, we are... we set very

00:47:02.330 --> 00:47:05.619
high standards with all of those
partners for safe performance.

00:47:05.619 --> 00:47:10.359
We have training videos for the
third parties that work with us

00:47:10.359 --> 00:47:14.430
to help them understand what we
expect in terms of the drive, we

00:47:14.430 --> 00:47:17.570
have mapping software that we
use to help them find the right

00:47:17.570 --> 00:47:18.570
routes.

00:47:18.570 --> 00:47:20.589
Every one of our drivers is

00:47:20.589 --> 00:47:23.020
required, including the third
parties, are required to have

00:47:23.020 --> 00:47:26.880
comprehensive insurance,
including liability insurance,

00:47:26.880 --> 00:47:33.240
so that if there is an accident
that the person who's injured is

00:47:33.240 --> 00:47:34.670
covered.

00:47:34.670 --> 00:47:35.670
&gt;&gt; Amazon wants to get Prime

00:47:35.670 --> 00:47:37.369
members their packages even
faster...

00:47:37.369 --> 00:47:40.680
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: In the last year,
Amazon announced a change to the

00:47:40.680 --> 00:47:43.150
way it handles Prime deliveries.

00:47:43.150 --> 00:47:44.930
Instead of delivering packages

00:47:44.930 --> 00:47:48.500
in two days, they promised to do
it in one.

00:47:48.500 --> 00:47:51.710
&gt;&gt; Free next-day delivery all
across the U.S....

00:47:51.710 --> 00:47:54.820
&gt;&gt; It's impossible for me to
imagine a world 20 years from

00:47:54.820 --> 00:47:57.410
now where a customer comes up
to me and says, "Jeff, I love

00:47:57.410 --> 00:47:58.410
Amazon.

00:47:58.410 --> 00:47:59.410
I just wish your prices were a

00:47:59.410 --> 00:48:00.410
little higher."

00:48:00.410 --> 00:48:01.410
Or, "I love Amazon.

00:48:01.410 --> 00:48:03.100
I just wish you delivered a
little more slowly."

00:48:03.100 --> 00:48:07.470
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: At the same time
the delivery network was being

00:48:07.470 --> 00:48:12.010
set up, Amazon was also rapidly
expanding its product offerings,

00:48:12.010 --> 00:48:14.700
inviting more sellers onto the
site.

00:48:14.700 --> 00:48:18.380
(computer plays tune)
Including those from China.

00:48:18.380 --> 00:48:23.200
&gt;&gt; It basically makes it to
where it's super-easy for these

00:48:23.200 --> 00:48:25.980
companies, who are maybe
not as careful with adhering to

00:48:25.980 --> 00:48:30.250
the law, where they're able to
just start a business up on

00:48:30.250 --> 00:48:35.520
Amazon, import some stuff, sell
it, cause some problems, and

00:48:35.520 --> 00:48:37.180
then disappear.

00:48:37.180 --> 00:48:39.119
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Rachel Greer worked

00:48:39.119 --> 00:48:42.740
in product safety at Amazon, and
worried that the site was being

00:48:42.740 --> 00:48:48.010
flooded with untested and
potentially unsafe products.

00:48:48.010 --> 00:48:49.760
&gt;&gt; Are there proper warnings?

00:48:49.760 --> 00:48:50.760
Has it been safety-tested for

00:48:50.760 --> 00:48:51.870
durability?

00:48:51.870 --> 00:48:53.171
If a child chews on it, will

00:48:53.171 --> 00:48:54.171
the paint come off?

00:48:54.171 --> 00:48:56.500
Is that paint leaded?

00:48:56.500 --> 00:48:59.829
&gt;&gt; Most people would
assume that there's a pretty

00:48:59.829 --> 00:49:02.980
high safety standard on Amazon.

00:49:02.980 --> 00:49:05.150
&gt;&gt; And that assumption would be

00:49:05.150 --> 00:49:06.150
incorrect.

00:49:06.150 --> 00:49:07.609
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: She says that's

00:49:07.609 --> 00:49:11.200
because Amazon, like other tech
companies, takes the position

00:49:11.200 --> 00:49:14.070
that it's not legally
responsible if its customers are

00:49:14.070 --> 00:49:18.220
harmed by products sold by third
parties on the site.

00:49:18.220 --> 00:49:22.020
&gt;&gt; If someone buys something
that causes harm at Walmart or

00:49:22.020 --> 00:49:25.770
at Target, a consumer can sue
Walmart or Target.

00:49:25.770 --> 00:49:27.319
&gt;&gt; Right, 'cause no one's
forcing you, when you come

00:49:27.319 --> 00:49:30.099
into Walmart, to enter the doors
of Walmart.

00:49:30.099 --> 00:49:32.820
They aren't making you sign
away your rights.

00:49:32.820 --> 00:49:35.650
&gt;&gt; But when do you sign
that when you go on Amazon.com?

00:49:35.650 --> 00:49:36.650
&gt;&gt; When you make your account.

00:49:36.650 --> 00:49:38.090
When you accept the terms and

00:49:38.090 --> 00:49:39.819
conditions.

00:49:39.819 --> 00:49:41.960
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: People have been

00:49:41.960 --> 00:49:45.390
challenging Amazon's terms and
conditions in court.

00:49:45.390 --> 00:49:48.599
Some have even been successful.

00:49:48.599 --> 00:49:51.480
&gt;&gt; Ultimately, who's on the hook

00:49:51.480 --> 00:49:54.960
when a customer buys a
dangerous product on Amazon?

00:49:54.960 --> 00:49:57.320
Who takes ultimate
responsibility for that?

00:49:57.320 --> 00:49:59.819
&gt;&gt; Well, in the rare case where
that, where something like that

00:49:59.819 --> 00:50:03.130
happens, if it's a third-party
seller, the sale is by a

00:50:03.130 --> 00:50:06.920
third-party seller, and it is
the seller's responsibility to,

00:50:06.920 --> 00:50:09.980
to sell a legitimate product to
a customer, and then, when

00:50:09.980 --> 00:50:13.619
Amazon is the retailer, and we
sell a product to the, to a

00:50:13.619 --> 00:50:16.691
customer, then it's our
obligation to make sure that we

00:50:16.691 --> 00:50:20.350
understand the manufacturer and
the supply chain for that

00:50:20.350 --> 00:50:23.079
product and its, and its safety.

00:50:23.079 --> 00:50:24.109
&gt;&gt; But when the other

00:50:24.109 --> 00:50:28.850
sellers are selling in your
store, you're not responsible

00:50:28.850 --> 00:50:32.720
for it ultimately, if they're
selling your customer a

00:50:32.720 --> 00:50:34.480
defective or dangerous product?

00:50:34.480 --> 00:50:36.090
&gt;&gt; I think the way things work

00:50:36.090 --> 00:50:41.440
in the U.S. is that the seller
of record is the person who is

00:50:41.440 --> 00:50:45.970
setting the price and who is
purchasing the product, and for

00:50:45.970 --> 00:50:49.340
things not sold by Amazon-- and
it says on the detail page,

00:50:49.340 --> 00:50:52.010
it'll tell you who the seller
is-- it's the seller's

00:50:52.010 --> 00:50:56.730
responsibility for those things,
and for us, it's very clear.

00:50:56.730 --> 00:50:59.589
It says Amazon.com whenever we
sell it.

00:50:59.589 --> 00:51:01.820
&gt;&gt; Do you audit your
sellers in terms of whether

00:51:01.820 --> 00:51:06.510
they're actually providing safe
products to your customers?

00:51:06.510 --> 00:51:07.510
&gt;&gt; We do...

00:51:07.510 --> 00:51:08.660
You know, some of our sales...

00:51:08.660 --> 00:51:13.250
So about, almost 60% of our
sales are by third parties,

00:51:13.250 --> 00:51:17.050
and those sales, some of them
come directly from the third

00:51:17.050 --> 00:51:18.840
party, so we're not involved
at all.

00:51:18.840 --> 00:51:19.840
&gt;&gt; But you take a cut.

00:51:19.840 --> 00:51:21.100
I mean, it's on your

00:51:21.100 --> 00:51:24.170
infrastructure, it goes through
Amazon.com, so, I mean...

00:51:24.170 --> 00:51:26.150
&gt;&gt; Well, it's on our
infrastructure in terms of the

00:51:26.150 --> 00:51:28.360
website and payments, but we're
not...

00:51:28.360 --> 00:51:31.349
&gt;&gt; And fees that, you
know, you're taking a cut of the

00:51:31.349 --> 00:51:32.490
sale, right?

00:51:32.490 --> 00:51:34.589
&gt;&gt; Sure, sure, and we're

00:51:34.589 --> 00:51:36.490
providing, you know, traffic
that, that...

00:51:36.490 --> 00:51:38.730
You know, it's kind of the way
they think about marketing is

00:51:38.730 --> 00:51:41.950
why they would pay that fee,
but...

00:51:41.950 --> 00:51:48.550
It's harder to, before an
experience, inspect that, that

00:51:48.550 --> 00:51:50.040
product.

00:51:50.040 --> 00:51:51.040
&gt;&gt; A South Carolina woman who

00:51:51.040 --> 00:51:53.809
bought a hair dryer on Amazon
said this happened.

00:51:53.809 --> 00:51:56.200
&gt;&gt; Fire is coming out of the
hair dryer.

00:51:56.200 --> 00:51:58.520
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Amazon's approach
has had consequences.

00:51:58.520 --> 00:52:01.450
&gt;&gt; A hoverboard caused a fire
that destroyed their home.

00:52:01.450 --> 00:52:04.040
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Dangerous products
were flagged by authorities in

00:52:04.040 --> 00:52:05.180
Washington State.

00:52:05.180 --> 00:52:06.180
&gt;&gt; ...found dozens of school

00:52:06.180 --> 00:52:08.839
supplies that had high levels
of toxic metals.

00:52:08.839 --> 00:52:12.210
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: And a recent report
found thousands of banned,

00:52:12.210 --> 00:52:14.410
unsafe, or mislabeled products.

00:52:14.410 --> 00:52:16.670
&gt;&gt; I'm having a hard time

00:52:16.670 --> 00:52:20.350
understanding something, which
is that, that...

00:52:20.350 --> 00:52:24.950
You know, Amazon's entire brand
is about the customer, right?

00:52:24.950 --> 00:52:25.950
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:52:25.950 --> 00:52:26.950
&gt;&gt; That it's...

00:52:26.950 --> 00:52:29.240
&gt;&gt; Oh, I reminded them of this
over and over again.

00:52:29.240 --> 00:52:31.119
&gt;&gt; You reminded them of
what?

00:52:31.119 --> 00:52:34.340
&gt;&gt; I said that no customer
wants to buy an unsafe product.

00:52:34.340 --> 00:52:36.930
No customer wants selection
that harms their child.

00:52:36.930 --> 00:52:38.670
No customer wants to buy
something that burns down their

00:52:38.670 --> 00:52:43.449
house because it looks cool and
it's the latest, coolest thing.

00:52:43.449 --> 00:52:46.339
&gt;&gt; Sitting here today,
are you able to basically say

00:52:46.339 --> 00:52:50.529
that the products that you sell
on Amazon.com are safe?

00:52:50.529 --> 00:52:54.030
&gt;&gt; What I can say is, we work
really hard to make sure that

00:52:54.030 --> 00:52:55.030
they're safe.

00:52:55.030 --> 00:52:56.030
We have...

00:52:56.030 --> 00:53:01.140
We've spent $400 million in the
last year on systems that seek

00:53:01.140 --> 00:53:04.450
out things that are not safe,
and, you know, there are

00:53:04.450 --> 00:53:08.020
millions of sellers and hundreds
of millions of products, and

00:53:08.020 --> 00:53:11.359
our job is to, as fast as we
can, weed out the ones that

00:53:11.359 --> 00:53:12.359
don't belong on our site.

00:53:12.359 --> 00:53:13.359
We're going to have to be

00:53:13.359 --> 00:53:16.980
vigilant as a retailer and as a
technology company, and we are

00:53:16.980 --> 00:53:20.590
definitely dedicated to, to
protecting the safety of our

00:53:20.590 --> 00:53:21.590
customers.

00:53:21.590 --> 00:53:22.590
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: We heard that

00:53:22.590 --> 00:53:25.540
concern for the customer over
and over in our interviews with

00:53:25.540 --> 00:53:27.330
Amazon executives.

00:53:27.330 --> 00:53:29.260
&gt;&gt; Customer trust in a company

00:53:29.260 --> 00:53:31.829
like Amazon, it's sort of
foundational.

00:53:31.829 --> 00:53:34.330
&gt;&gt; Customer obsession is the
first leadership principle, and

00:53:34.330 --> 00:53:36.599
it, it's not a corporate slogan.

00:53:36.599 --> 00:53:38.349
&gt;&gt; We try to stay really focused

00:53:38.349 --> 00:53:39.370
on customers.

00:53:39.370 --> 00:53:40.990
&gt;&gt; Very focused on, on

00:53:40.990 --> 00:53:42.670
delivering results for our
customers.

00:53:42.670 --> 00:53:45.589
&gt;&gt; Providing a great customer
experience that customers want.

00:53:45.589 --> 00:53:48.089
&gt;&gt; Delivering that, that
customer delight.

00:53:48.089 --> 00:53:51.070
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: This commitment to
the customer, and to keeping

00:53:51.070 --> 00:53:55.050
prices low, had another benefit:
it helped them avoid running

00:53:55.050 --> 00:54:00.039
afoul of regulators who enforce
the nation's antitrust laws.

00:54:00.039 --> 00:54:02.589
&gt;&gt; It's important to understand
sort of that there's two

00:54:02.589 --> 00:54:06.650
fundamental philosophies of
antitrust, of anti-monopoly law.

00:54:06.650 --> 00:54:09.040
You know, there's the
traditional philosophy, in which

00:54:09.040 --> 00:54:13.570
you, you want to break up all
potential concentrations of

00:54:13.570 --> 00:54:15.250
power that you can.

00:54:15.250 --> 00:54:18.650
But for the last 30 years,

00:54:18.650 --> 00:54:21.290
there's been this change in how
we do antitrust.

00:54:21.290 --> 00:54:25.630
And this is the idea that the
only purpose of antitrust should

00:54:25.630 --> 00:54:31.230
be to drive prices lower, to
serve the interest of the

00:54:31.230 --> 00:54:33.359
consumer.

00:54:33.359 --> 00:54:35.980
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Lynn had been

00:54:35.980 --> 00:54:39.420
urging regulators to take a more
traditional approach and

00:54:39.420 --> 00:54:42.280
examine whether the company was
gaining market power in

00:54:42.280 --> 00:54:47.210
exploitative ways: stifling fair
competition, but keeping prices

00:54:47.210 --> 00:54:50.010
low for consumers.

00:54:50.010 --> 00:54:51.890
&gt;&gt; We live in a society

00:54:51.890 --> 00:54:55.200
of consumers, though, and
seemingly there is some net

00:54:55.200 --> 00:54:58.770
benefit to all of us when
prices are low.

00:54:58.770 --> 00:55:01.299
So, what's wrong with that view
of things?

00:55:01.299 --> 00:55:03.980
&gt;&gt; It's obviously good for
people to... for all people if

00:55:03.980 --> 00:55:07.050
we can drive down prices, if we
have lower-priced drugs, if we

00:55:07.050 --> 00:55:10.079
have books that anybody could
buy.

00:55:10.079 --> 00:55:11.079
That's a good thing.

00:55:11.079 --> 00:55:12.079
It's a good thing for society,

00:55:12.079 --> 00:55:15.309
and it's a good thing for us as
consumers.

00:55:15.309 --> 00:55:19.310
But we're not only consumers,
we're also citizens.

00:55:19.310 --> 00:55:20.720
We're also producers.

00:55:20.720 --> 00:55:22.720
We're also people who think and

00:55:22.720 --> 00:55:27.200
who make things and who grow
things, and we want to have

00:55:27.200 --> 00:55:29.150
access to open markets.

00:55:29.150 --> 00:55:31.369
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Once again, the

00:55:31.369 --> 00:55:35.490
tension was most pronounced
with book publishers.

00:55:35.490 --> 00:55:39.079
Amazon was selling around 40%
of all new books in America

00:55:39.079 --> 00:55:42.740
and two-thirds of all electronic
books, thanks to the success of

00:55:42.740 --> 00:55:44.010
the Kindle.

00:55:44.010 --> 00:55:46.770
Then, one of the world's largest

00:55:46.770 --> 00:55:50.020
publishers, Hachette, decided to
push back.

00:55:50.020 --> 00:55:53.240
Franklin Foer was one of its
authors.

00:55:53.240 --> 00:55:58.120
&gt;&gt; Hachette and Amazon set out
to renegotiate their e-book

00:55:58.120 --> 00:55:59.120
contract.

00:55:59.120 --> 00:56:00.680
And Hachette said, "No, we don't

00:56:00.680 --> 00:56:03.130
accept the terms of your
contract."

00:56:03.130 --> 00:56:06.460
And Amazon basically said, "To
hell with you, Hachette.

00:56:06.460 --> 00:56:08.839
We're going to stop delivering
your books.

00:56:08.839 --> 00:56:11.540
If somebody searches for a
Hachette title, we're going to

00:56:11.540 --> 00:56:13.609
redirect them to another
publisher."

00:56:13.609 --> 00:56:17.760
&gt;&gt; Amazon's battle with Hachette
and the authors that Hachette

00:56:17.760 --> 00:56:19.230
publishes is heating up.

00:56:19.230 --> 00:56:21.120
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: As Bezos's virtual

00:56:21.120 --> 00:56:23.420
blockade dragged on for months.

00:56:23.420 --> 00:56:24.710
&gt;&gt; A bitter, seven-month

00:56:24.710 --> 00:56:26.030
standoff...

00:56:26.030 --> 00:56:27.349
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Thousands of

00:56:27.349 --> 00:56:30.230
authors, including bestsellers
like Douglas Preston, were

00:56:30.230 --> 00:56:31.940
caught in the middle.

00:56:31.940 --> 00:56:33.809
&gt;&gt; Some authors were losing 50%

00:56:33.809 --> 00:56:37.559
to 90% of their sales from
Amazon.

00:56:37.559 --> 00:56:41.780
It was absolutely devastating
to first-time authors.

00:56:41.780 --> 00:56:45.950
It actually destroyed their
careers.

00:56:45.950 --> 00:56:47.390
&gt;&gt; Did you see your
sales plummet?

00:56:47.390 --> 00:56:48.390
&gt;&gt; I did, yes.

00:56:48.390 --> 00:56:49.740
I saw my sales plummet

00:56:49.740 --> 00:56:50.740
tremendously.

00:56:50.740 --> 00:56:53.510
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: In frustration,

00:56:53.510 --> 00:56:57.130
Preston penned an open letter
on behalf of all authors.

00:56:57.130 --> 00:57:01.020
It was published in "The New
York Times" with more than 900

00:57:01.020 --> 00:57:02.380
signatures.

00:57:02.380 --> 00:57:04.490
&gt;&gt; We authors have loved Amazon.

00:57:04.490 --> 00:57:07.700
We have enthusiastically
supported it, and this is how

00:57:07.700 --> 00:57:09.070
they treat us?

00:57:09.070 --> 00:57:11.480
This is not right.

00:57:11.480 --> 00:57:13.990
&gt;&gt; Amazon has been accused of
doing everything from raising

00:57:13.990 --> 00:57:15.940
prices to deliberately delaying
shipments.

00:57:15.940 --> 00:57:18.720
&gt;&gt; Is this what happens when
Jeff Bezos decides to flex his

00:57:18.720 --> 00:57:19.720
muscles?

00:57:19.720 --> 00:57:20.720
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: While Hachette and

00:57:20.720 --> 00:57:24.450
Amazon were at an impasse,
Douglas Preston, Franklin Foer,

00:57:24.450 --> 00:57:28.100
and other authors went to
Washington, and asked the Obama

00:57:28.100 --> 00:57:30.910
administration to open an
investigation.

00:57:30.910 --> 00:57:33.690
&gt;&gt; I went to the Justice
Department and I went to the

00:57:33.690 --> 00:57:37.030
Federal Trade Commission with
the Authors Guild, and we tried

00:57:37.030 --> 00:57:41.420
to explain to them why this
power was so dangerous.

00:57:41.420 --> 00:57:44.280
We pointed it out of all the
ways in which Amazon was

00:57:44.280 --> 00:57:46.920
bullying the publishing
industry.

00:57:46.920 --> 00:57:50.480
&gt;&gt; The Department of Justice
listened to us.

00:57:50.480 --> 00:57:55.690
And their answer was essentially
this: "Amazon is one of the most

00:57:55.690 --> 00:57:58.589
popular companies in the
country.

00:57:58.589 --> 00:58:01.569
(camera clicks)
They have brought tremendous

00:58:01.569 --> 00:58:06.230
services to consumers, and
they've brought lower prices."

00:58:06.230 --> 00:58:08.830
And that we hadn't given them
any kind of reason to open an

00:58:08.830 --> 00:58:10.150
antitrust investigation.

00:58:10.150 --> 00:58:11.700
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Eventually,

00:58:11.700 --> 00:58:15.640
Hachette and Amazon would
settle their dispute, with

00:58:15.640 --> 00:58:19.119
Amazon allowing Hachette to set
its own prices for e-books, but

00:58:19.119 --> 00:58:21.680
offering it incentives to keep
them low.

00:58:21.680 --> 00:58:26.250
&gt;&gt; It's great to be here at
Amazon.

00:58:26.250 --> 00:58:29.000
(crowd cheering)
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Amazon would thrive

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:32.569
during the Obama years, and
eventually account for nearly

00:58:32.569 --> 00:58:35.960
40% of all online commerce in
the country.

00:58:35.960 --> 00:58:40.410
&gt;&gt; Last year, during the busiest
day of the Christmas rush,

00:58:40.410 --> 00:58:44.740
customers around the world
ordered more than 300 items from

00:58:44.740 --> 00:58:46.390
Amazon every second.

00:58:46.390 --> 00:58:47.859
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: But the complaints

00:58:47.859 --> 00:58:51.250
about its tactics would
continue, with retailers of all

00:58:51.250 --> 00:58:54.690
kinds concerned that Amazon had
become the online-shopping

00:58:54.690 --> 00:58:55.690
gatekeeper.

00:58:55.690 --> 00:58:58.410
&gt;&gt; You've got to be on Amazon.

00:58:58.410 --> 00:59:01.770
You have to be there, because
that's where everyone is.

00:59:01.770 --> 00:59:02.770
That...

00:59:02.770 --> 00:59:05.530
100 million Prime
subscribers.

00:59:05.530 --> 00:59:09.000
They are the de facto e-commerce
channel in the United States,

00:59:09.000 --> 00:59:11.980
period, end of list.

00:59:11.980 --> 00:59:12.980
&gt;&gt; Amazon executives

00:59:12.980 --> 00:59:16.990
have told us that there are many
other options out there.

00:59:16.990 --> 00:59:19.430
There is Walmart, there is
Alibaba.

00:59:19.430 --> 00:59:21.440
As a seller, you've got options.

00:59:21.440 --> 00:59:24.130
&gt;&gt; I've heard that response from

00:59:24.130 --> 00:59:28.559
Amazon executives before, and we
did that, we were listed, we

00:59:28.559 --> 00:59:32.619
listed all of our products on
every other online marketplace.

00:59:32.619 --> 00:59:37.250
But it's a testament to just
how good Amazon is.

00:59:37.250 --> 00:59:41.150
All of the others that were
non-Amazon combined did about

00:59:41.150 --> 00:59:45.020
ten percent of what we were
doing on Amazon.

00:59:45.020 --> 00:59:48.270
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Businesses big and
small have been accumulating

00:59:48.270 --> 00:59:51.109
complaints about Amazon's hold
on them.

00:59:51.109 --> 00:59:54.720
&gt;&gt; On Amazon, the customer
belongs to Amazon-- it doesn't

00:59:54.720 --> 00:59:56.480
belong to the third-party
seller.

00:59:56.480 --> 00:59:58.969
You're basically renting the
Amazon customer.

00:59:58.969 --> 01:00:01.839
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: James Thomson used
to recruit brands to come onto

01:00:01.839 --> 01:00:05.770
Amazon and now advises them on
how to do business with the

01:00:05.770 --> 01:00:06.770
company.

01:00:06.770 --> 01:00:08.780
&gt;&gt; I represent brands today that

01:00:08.780 --> 01:00:11.349
face a number of challenges with
Amazon.

01:00:11.349 --> 01:00:14.270
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Among those
challenges, businesses say that

01:00:14.270 --> 01:00:17.860
Amazon has access to their
valuable data, which gives it an

01:00:17.860 --> 01:00:19.089
unfair advantage.

01:00:19.089 --> 01:00:20.480
They also complain about

01:00:20.480 --> 01:00:24.349
increasingly higher fees to stay
on the platform, and pressure to

01:00:24.349 --> 01:00:30.780
use Amazon's warehouses and
shipping services.

01:00:30.780 --> 01:00:34.069
We spoke to numerous name-brand
companies, but none would share

01:00:34.069 --> 01:00:36.160
its grievances on camera.

01:00:36.160 --> 01:00:38.170
&gt;&gt; My account was suspended.

01:00:38.170 --> 01:00:39.809
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Some small
businesspeople have been

01:00:39.809 --> 01:00:42.300
talking about their
experiences-- good and bad--

01:00:42.300 --> 01:00:43.300
online.

01:00:43.300 --> 01:00:44.300
&gt;&gt; When you're selling on

01:00:44.300 --> 01:00:47.180
Amazon, you're playing in
someone else's playground.

01:00:47.180 --> 01:00:51.569
&gt;&gt; Who gets placed where,
whether or not your product

01:00:51.569 --> 01:00:52.990
shows up in the search
results...

01:00:52.990 --> 01:00:54.920
&gt;&gt; They suspended my account
without warning.

01:00:54.920 --> 01:00:59.250
&gt;&gt; These are all things that are
governed by Amazon's rules.

01:00:59.250 --> 01:01:02.490
And if there's a dispute within
that arena, if you feel you are

01:01:02.490 --> 01:01:05.690
mistreated, you know, the judge
and jury is Amazon.

01:01:05.690 --> 01:01:09.010
&gt;&gt; They don't care, they'll just
kill your account like that or

01:01:09.010 --> 01:01:10.010
suspend it...

01:01:10.010 --> 01:01:11.069
&gt;&gt; There are all sorts of crazy

01:01:11.069 --> 01:01:14.980
stories about why people get
their accounts shut down on

01:01:14.980 --> 01:01:15.980
Amazon.

01:01:15.980 --> 01:01:16.980
And it could take a week, it

01:01:16.980 --> 01:01:18.330
could take months, it could be
never before you're back online

01:01:18.330 --> 01:01:19.710
again.

01:01:19.710 --> 01:01:21.430
Amazon has the upper hand and

01:01:21.430 --> 01:01:26.880
the ability to basically take
your business away from you at

01:01:26.880 --> 01:01:28.440
any given moment.

01:01:28.440 --> 01:01:31.140
&gt;&gt; Selling on Amazon, take one.

01:01:31.140 --> 01:01:33.520
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Amazon said
third-party sellers account for

01:01:33.520 --> 01:01:36.109
more than half of everything
sold on the site.

01:01:36.109 --> 01:01:38.400
&gt;&gt; I sell mini-longboard
skateboards.

01:01:38.400 --> 01:01:39.420
&gt;&gt; I sell mineral water.

01:01:39.420 --> 01:01:40.420
This is what I do.

01:01:40.420 --> 01:01:41.720
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: And it's
committed to its sellers'

01:01:41.720 --> 01:01:45.849
success-- proactively contacting
them when their accounts are at

01:01:45.849 --> 01:01:49.930
risk of suspension and offering
an appeals process to resolve

01:01:49.930 --> 01:01:50.930
disputes.

01:01:50.930 --> 01:01:52.270
&gt;&gt; You already have great

01:01:52.270 --> 01:01:53.270
products.

01:01:53.270 --> 01:01:54.270
Scale up...

01:01:54.270 --> 01:01:56.720
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: But in the eyes of
some businesses, Amazon has

01:01:56.720 --> 01:01:59.240
essentially become like the
railroads at the turn of the

01:01:59.240 --> 01:02:03.079
last century that controlled
the flow of commerce across the

01:02:03.079 --> 01:02:04.079
country.

01:02:04.079 --> 01:02:06.180
&gt;&gt; Start selling today.

01:02:06.180 --> 01:02:08.980
&gt;&gt; Do you see yourself
as being kind of like the rails

01:02:08.980 --> 01:02:12.890
for e-commerce, that sellers
bring their goods to market

01:02:12.890 --> 01:02:14.820
on your rails, through your
marketplace?

01:02:14.820 --> 01:02:19.600
&gt;&gt; I don't think of it that way,
and here's why: the, the vast

01:02:19.600 --> 01:02:21.080
majority of stuff that's...

01:02:21.080 --> 01:02:22.080
Well, all of the stuff that's

01:02:22.080 --> 01:02:23.340
sold is manufactured, right?

01:02:23.340 --> 01:02:24.970
So it's manufactured, meaning

01:02:24.970 --> 01:02:28.640
there are brands and factories
that produce stuff and then sell

01:02:28.640 --> 01:02:30.240
it.

01:02:30.240 --> 01:02:32.460
We're one percent of the retail

01:02:32.460 --> 01:02:34.060
sales in the world, about.

01:02:34.060 --> 01:02:35.160
&gt;&gt; Well, you are the

01:02:35.160 --> 01:02:36.940
biggest marketplace online,
right?

01:02:36.940 --> 01:02:39.510
&gt;&gt; No, so, again, I, I don't...

01:02:39.510 --> 01:02:43.390
The idea that there's an online,

01:02:43.390 --> 01:02:45.790
distinct for brands to sell
their stuff and distinct from

01:02:45.790 --> 01:02:49.710
physical, just doesn't make
sense to me, and we're far from

01:02:49.710 --> 01:02:51.099
the largest retailer.

01:02:51.099 --> 01:02:53.440
So, I, I describe this as

01:02:53.440 --> 01:02:56.180
retail, and we're competing
against Walmart and Target and

01:02:56.180 --> 01:03:00.349
Costco and Carrefour and Alibaba
and Tmall and all kinds of folks

01:03:00.349 --> 01:03:05.830
who are, are now selling both
physical stores and online.

01:03:05.830 --> 01:03:09.210
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: In addition to
pointing to other large

01:03:09.210 --> 01:03:12.400
retailers, inside the company
employees have been

01:03:12.400 --> 01:03:17.189
schooled in how to talk about
its size and power.

01:03:17.189 --> 01:03:19.799
&gt;&gt; When I worked at Amazon, we
had training specifically on the

01:03:19.799 --> 01:03:22.770
use of terms like "monopoly."

01:03:22.770 --> 01:03:23.830
We were not allowed to use a

01:03:23.830 --> 01:03:26.440
term like "market share."

01:03:26.440 --> 01:03:27.640
Amazon has what's known as

01:03:27.640 --> 01:03:29.720
"market segment share."

01:03:29.720 --> 01:03:31.299
What is market segment?

01:03:31.299 --> 01:03:32.630
What is market segment share?

01:03:32.630 --> 01:03:34.230
I don't know, but I know that

01:03:34.230 --> 01:03:38.090
the lawyers at Amazon feel those
terms are, are much safer than

01:03:38.090 --> 01:03:40.040
using terms like market share.

01:03:40.040 --> 01:03:41.040
&gt;&gt; So market share was

01:03:41.040 --> 01:03:42.940
something they were really
concerned about.

01:03:42.940 --> 01:03:48.020
&gt;&gt; Clearly somebody with the
necessary legal training or PR

01:03:48.020 --> 01:03:51.960
training recognized that Amazon
was growing very quickly, and

01:03:51.960 --> 01:03:56.400
when we were asked to use the
term "market segment" and

01:03:56.400 --> 01:04:00.300
"market segment share," in
essence it's a polite way of

01:04:00.300 --> 01:04:03.349
saying, "I'm not going to talk
to you about how big we are."

01:04:03.349 --> 01:04:07.880
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Since leaving
Amazon 20 years ago, Shel

01:04:07.880 --> 01:04:10.890
Kaphan has been watching the
company with increasing

01:04:10.890 --> 01:04:14.720
concern, and he's speaking
about it for the first time.

01:04:14.720 --> 01:04:17.630
&gt;&gt; I think that the
characterization of Amazon as

01:04:17.630 --> 01:04:25.000
being a ruthless competitor is
true, and under the flag of

01:04:25.000 --> 01:04:28.829
customer obsession, they can do
a lot of things which might not

01:04:28.829 --> 01:04:31.980
be good for people who aren't
their customers.

01:04:31.980 --> 01:04:34.490
&gt;&gt; I know you're not a
legal scholar, but are you

01:04:34.490 --> 01:04:37.579
basically concerned that Amazon
is a monopoly?

01:04:37.579 --> 01:04:41.290
&gt;&gt; I'm, I'm concerned that it
has that type of power.

01:04:41.290 --> 01:04:43.910
I think it, you know, whether
you technically can call it a

01:04:43.910 --> 01:04:49.740
monopoly or not, I don't know.

01:04:49.740 --> 01:04:50.740
♪ ♪

01:04:50.740 --> 01:04:55.260
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: That question has
continued to loom over Amazon.

01:04:55.260 --> 01:04:58.819
&gt;&gt; I think that Amazon is
looking out, and the existential

01:04:58.819 --> 01:05:03.900
threat that they may face is
going to be from government.

01:05:03.900 --> 01:05:06.380
It's whether or not
policymakers are going to step

01:05:06.380 --> 01:05:10.349
in and intervene and say, "You
have too much power."

01:05:10.349 --> 01:05:14.220
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: For years, Bezos
has been ramping up Amazon's

01:05:14.220 --> 01:05:17.240
profile in Washington.

01:05:17.240 --> 01:05:18.349
&gt;&gt; Amazon has been lobbying the

01:05:18.349 --> 01:05:19.349
F.A.A. to lift...

01:05:19.349 --> 01:05:20.349
&gt;&gt; Trying to cozy up to

01:05:20.349 --> 01:05:24.000
politicians, so that they will
give him the biggest tax breaks

01:05:24.000 --> 01:05:25.000
around...

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:26.000
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Spending millions a

01:05:26.000 --> 01:05:27.000
year on lobbying.

01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:28.000
&gt;&gt; Amazon lobbied more

01:05:28.000 --> 01:05:30.960
government entities than any
other tech company.

01:05:30.960 --> 01:05:32.890
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: And hiring as its
spokesman the former White House

01:05:32.890 --> 01:05:35.010
press secretary Jay Carney.

01:05:35.010 --> 01:05:37.460
&gt;&gt; You've got an army of

01:05:37.460 --> 01:05:39.690
lobbyists, many of whom have
revolved in and out of

01:05:39.690 --> 01:05:41.780
government, including yourself.

01:05:41.780 --> 01:05:43.110
What are you hoping to get for

01:05:43.110 --> 01:05:46.809
all that lobbying spend and all
that influence?

01:05:46.809 --> 01:05:48.520
&gt;&gt; One of the things we
discovered is, because of the

01:05:48.520 --> 01:05:51.440
visibility of our company, but
also the range of businesses

01:05:51.440 --> 01:05:54.900
that we're in, we need
subject-matter experts on food

01:05:54.900 --> 01:05:59.930
safety, on transportation, on
drones, on privacy.

01:05:59.930 --> 01:06:03.319
And also, we can be a resource,
an information provider to

01:06:03.319 --> 01:06:04.860
policymakers and regulators.

01:06:04.860 --> 01:06:06.160
It's not lobbying in the

01:06:06.160 --> 01:06:08.400
traditional sense, in terms of
trying to persuade somebody to

01:06:08.400 --> 01:06:11.059
do something, it's just
answering questions and, and

01:06:11.059 --> 01:06:14.150
providing data and information.

01:06:14.150 --> 01:06:16.780
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Bezos himself would

01:06:16.780 --> 01:06:21.030
also become a presence in the
capital, and eventually buy the

01:06:21.030 --> 01:06:24.170
largest private residence in
town.

01:06:24.170 --> 01:06:27.290
&gt;&gt; Jeff Bezos never really
showed much interest in

01:06:27.290 --> 01:06:31.150
politics, but as he's cemented
himself in the city, he's

01:06:31.150 --> 01:06:33.950
started to acquire this physical
presence.

01:06:33.950 --> 01:06:37.650
He bought a mansion, then
developed it into a place that

01:06:37.650 --> 01:06:40.470
is explicitly designed to be
social.

01:06:40.470 --> 01:06:44.059
&gt;&gt; It has a big ballroom, I
mean, it is designed to create a

01:06:44.059 --> 01:06:48.109
real presence for him in the
nation's capital, where he can

01:06:48.109 --> 01:06:50.860
hobnob with the people who make
decisions.

01:06:50.860 --> 01:06:54.579
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: He'd even bought
the hometown newspaper...

01:06:54.579 --> 01:06:57.440
&gt;&gt; Jeff Bezos sent a thunderbolt
through the media world this

01:06:57.440 --> 01:06:58.440
week...

01:06:58.440 --> 01:06:59.440
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Spending a quarter

01:06:59.440 --> 01:07:02.109
of a billion dollars to rescue
the struggling "Washington

01:07:02.109 --> 01:07:03.109
Post."

01:07:03.109 --> 01:07:04.410
&gt;&gt; I do believe that democracy

01:07:04.410 --> 01:07:05.549
dies in darkness.

01:07:05.549 --> 01:07:07.280
I think that the capital city

01:07:07.280 --> 01:07:11.349
of the United States of America
needs a paper like "The

01:07:11.349 --> 01:07:12.349
Washington Post."

01:07:12.349 --> 01:07:14.359
&gt;&gt; I got to say, you know, full

01:07:14.359 --> 01:07:18.400
credit to him, he hasn't
intervened in any of the

01:07:18.400 --> 01:07:20.630
coverage of the paper.

01:07:20.630 --> 01:07:22.470
And he's invested in the paper.

01:07:22.470 --> 01:07:27.470
Every dollar of profit that the
paper makes is plowed back into

01:07:27.470 --> 01:07:29.579
making it a better paper.

01:07:29.579 --> 01:07:33.000
&gt;&gt; Bezos allowed the "Post" to

01:07:33.000 --> 01:07:36.320
hire, to restock its newsroom,
he reversed what had been an

01:07:36.320 --> 01:07:38.670
atmosphere of sort of decline.

01:07:38.670 --> 01:07:39.670
I'd say "The Washington Post"

01:07:39.670 --> 01:07:42.440
has really flourished under,
under Bezos's ownership.

01:07:42.440 --> 01:07:45.290
&gt;&gt; Let's cut this digital
ribbon.

01:07:45.290 --> 01:07:48.819
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: At the time,
critics saw a more cynical

01:07:48.819 --> 01:07:49.819
motive.

01:07:49.819 --> 01:07:50.819
&gt;&gt; Perhaps he's buying "The

01:07:50.819 --> 01:07:53.110
Washington Post" to buy some
sort of protection.

01:07:53.110 --> 01:07:54.110
&gt;&gt; Precisely.

01:07:54.110 --> 01:07:55.280
&gt;&gt; This deal could give him more

01:07:55.280 --> 01:07:57.070
influence over politics.

01:07:57.070 --> 01:07:58.849
&gt;&gt; Nobody hangs out in

01:07:58.849 --> 01:08:04.010
Washington, DC, just to go to
the free museums.

01:08:04.010 --> 01:08:07.180
You buy a home in Washington,
you buy a newspaper in

01:08:07.180 --> 01:08:10.920
Washington, because it is the
most influential city in the

01:08:10.920 --> 01:08:15.999
world, and you want to lay your
hands on that power.

01:08:15.999 --> 01:08:18.359
♪ ♪
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Bezos saw a

01:08:18.359 --> 01:08:21.819
business opportunity there, as
well.

01:08:21.819 --> 01:08:25.159
The Obama administration planned
to modernize the federal

01:08:25.159 --> 01:08:28.929
government by embracing cloud
computing.

01:08:28.929 --> 01:08:32.589
Bezos had been quietly building
a revolutionary cloud computing

01:08:32.589 --> 01:08:33.589
business.

01:08:33.589 --> 01:08:35.669
He called it Amazon Web

01:08:35.669 --> 01:08:37.949
Services.

01:08:37.949 --> 01:08:39.089
&gt;&gt; It's basically computing

01:08:39.089 --> 01:08:42.519
power in the cloud, but really
it's Amazon's server farms

01:08:42.519 --> 01:08:46.190
around the world that give
people access to the kind of

01:08:46.190 --> 01:08:48.630
technology services they need.

01:08:48.630 --> 01:08:50.409
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: To keep Amazon

01:08:50.409 --> 01:08:53.889
running, Bezos had developed an
unprecedented digital

01:08:53.889 --> 01:08:54.889
infrastructure.

01:08:54.889 --> 01:08:56.929
He realized he could rent parts

01:08:56.929 --> 01:09:01.019
of it out, not just to
businesses, but also to the

01:09:01.019 --> 01:09:03.449
government.

01:09:03.449 --> 01:09:04.540
&gt;&gt; Our infrastructure is built

01:09:04.540 --> 01:09:07.289
to satisfy the security
standards of the most

01:09:07.289 --> 01:09:09.109
risk-sensitive organizations.

01:09:09.109 --> 01:09:10.880
&gt;&gt; He's already got a huge edge

01:09:10.880 --> 01:09:13.589
over the other big competitors
in it.

01:09:13.589 --> 01:09:18.479
So he wants to take that lead
and capture the U.S. government.

01:09:18.479 --> 01:09:23.349
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: In 2013, he got a
major boost when it was

01:09:23.349 --> 01:09:26.019
revealed that Amazon Web
Services had designed a

01:09:26.019 --> 01:09:30.469
computing cloud for the C.I.A.

01:09:30.469 --> 01:09:31.469
&gt;&gt; Amazon Web Services was

01:09:31.469 --> 01:09:34.949
awarded a ten-year contract for
$600 million.

01:09:34.949 --> 01:09:37.429
&gt;&gt; Amazon is helping the C.I.A.
build a secure cloud computer

01:09:37.429 --> 01:09:38.429
network...

01:09:38.429 --> 01:09:39.449
&gt;&gt; The C.I.A. contract was

01:09:39.449 --> 01:09:42.309
probably one of the best things
that happened to Amazon's cloud

01:09:42.309 --> 01:09:43.309
business.

01:09:43.309 --> 01:09:45.409
It lifted all doubts about the

01:09:45.409 --> 01:09:49.080
security of the cloud and on
whether you could trust Amazon

01:09:49.080 --> 01:09:51.139
with your most precious data.

01:09:51.139 --> 01:09:53.269
&gt;&gt; The message to the world is,

01:09:53.269 --> 01:09:56.369
"If the C.I.A. trusts Amazon
with its data, then maybe other

01:09:56.369 --> 01:09:59.860
companies and government
institutions can, as well."

01:09:59.860 --> 01:10:01.820
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: And they did.

01:10:01.820 --> 01:10:03.100
&gt;&gt; Experience it with Expedia.

01:10:03.100 --> 01:10:05.829
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: A.W.S. became by
far the world's leading

01:10:05.829 --> 01:10:07.260
cloud-computing platform.

01:10:07.260 --> 01:10:08.369
&gt;&gt; On CBS.

01:10:08.369 --> 01:10:12.340
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Today, more than a
million businesses, as well as

01:10:12.340 --> 01:10:16.469
PBS, pay Amazon to
store and manage their data.

01:10:16.469 --> 01:10:20.429
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Bezos had again
anticipated the next frontier in

01:10:20.429 --> 01:10:24.579
technology, and had made himself
indispensable to it.

01:10:24.579 --> 01:10:28.079
&gt;&gt; What Jeff Bezos is after is
really creating a company that

01:10:28.079 --> 01:10:31.479
is the infrastructure, that owns
the infrastructure for how

01:10:31.479 --> 01:10:33.889
commerce is done.

01:10:33.889 --> 01:10:35.010
And that's an incredibly

01:10:35.010 --> 01:10:37.539
powerful place to be.

01:10:37.539 --> 01:10:38.539
♪ ♪

01:10:38.539 --> 01:10:42.619
&gt;&gt; Please welcome chief
executive officer of Amazon Web

01:10:42.619 --> 01:10:44.179
Services Andy Jassy.

01:10:44.179 --> 01:10:46.050
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Andy Jassy created

01:10:46.050 --> 01:10:47.770
and runs A.W.S.

01:10:47.770 --> 01:10:49.480
He credits the service with

01:10:49.480 --> 01:10:52.900
making it easier to do business
and sparking innovation

01:10:52.900 --> 01:10:54.199
throughout the economy.

01:10:54.199 --> 01:10:57.190
&gt;&gt; Look at what A.W.S. has

01:10:57.190 --> 01:10:59.760
enabled with regard to change
in our society.

01:10:59.760 --> 01:11:04.330
Look at, Netflix changed the way
that we consume digital content,

01:11:04.330 --> 01:11:09.219
and Airbnb changed the way that
we get accommodations, and Hola

01:11:09.219 --> 01:11:12.169
and Grab and Lyft and Uber
changed the way that we get

01:11:12.169 --> 01:11:13.169
transportation.

01:11:13.169 --> 01:11:15.499
A.W.S. has enabled, has been a

01:11:15.499 --> 01:11:20.760
part of enabling all these huge
innovations and changes in

01:11:20.760 --> 01:11:23.659
consumer experiences that
have, have made life better for

01:11:23.659 --> 01:11:24.659
people.

01:11:24.659 --> 01:11:26.190
&gt;&gt; And we're the cloud with the

01:11:26.190 --> 01:11:29.389
most capabilities, the most
innovation, the most customers.

01:11:29.389 --> 01:11:32.739
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: The division
generated $35 billion in sales

01:11:32.739 --> 01:11:34.369
last year.

01:11:34.369 --> 01:11:35.940
&gt;&gt; Amazon Web Services.

01:11:35.940 --> 01:11:36.940
&gt;&gt; Yes!

01:11:36.940 --> 01:11:37.959
&gt;&gt; Build On.

01:11:37.959 --> 01:11:41.770
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: The success of
A.W.S. gave Bezos billions to

01:11:41.770 --> 01:11:45.699
expand Amazon from a company
that sells everything to a

01:11:45.699 --> 01:11:47.719
company that does everything.

01:11:47.719 --> 01:11:49.679
A top priority...

01:11:49.679 --> 01:11:54.779
&gt;&gt; To boldly go where no man has
gone before.

01:11:54.779 --> 01:11:58.369
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: ...was to create
the sci-fi future he'd fallen in

01:11:58.369 --> 01:12:01.109
love with as a child.

01:12:01.109 --> 01:12:03.860
&gt;&gt; Gentlemen, this computer has

01:12:03.860 --> 01:12:05.219
an auditory sensor.

01:12:05.219 --> 01:12:07.119
It can, in effect, hear sounds.

01:12:07.119 --> 01:12:10.280
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: A world of
artificial intelligence, in

01:12:10.280 --> 01:12:14.849
which computers can think and
make decisions for humans and

01:12:14.849 --> 01:12:16.409
about humans.

01:12:16.409 --> 01:12:17.749
&gt;&gt; Jeff Bezos is a big fan

01:12:17.749 --> 01:12:19.340
of "Star Trek."

01:12:19.340 --> 01:12:22.070
He, he admits that that was on

01:12:22.070 --> 01:12:26.959
his brain when he came up with
the idea that Amazon should be

01:12:26.959 --> 01:12:31.860
pursuing a little disk that you
can bark commands into.

01:12:31.860 --> 01:12:33.230
&gt;&gt; Stop.

01:12:33.230 --> 01:12:35.110
&gt;&gt; This is his "Beam me up,

01:12:35.110 --> 01:12:37.589
Scotty" fantasy realized.

01:12:37.589 --> 01:12:39.260
&gt;&gt; We started working on this

01:12:39.260 --> 01:12:40.260
device.

01:12:40.260 --> 01:12:44.360
And our, our vision was, in the

01:12:44.360 --> 01:12:46.019
long term, it would become the
Star Trek computer.

01:12:46.019 --> 01:12:49.369
&gt;&gt; When it first arrived from
Amazon, I didn't know what it

01:12:49.369 --> 01:12:50.369
was.

01:12:50.369 --> 01:12:52.239
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: In 2014, Bezos's

01:12:52.239 --> 01:12:55.419
talking computer, the Amazon
Echo, hit the market.

01:12:55.419 --> 01:12:56.829
&gt;&gt; Is it for me?

01:12:56.829 --> 01:12:57.889
&gt;&gt; It's for everyone.

01:12:57.889 --> 01:13:01.579
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: The voice known as
Alexa would embed Amazon deeper

01:13:01.579 --> 01:13:04.139
into the lives of millions of
people.

01:13:04.139 --> 01:13:05.639
&gt;&gt; Alexa, what do you do?

01:13:05.639 --> 01:13:08.060
&gt;&gt; I can play music, answer

01:13:08.060 --> 01:13:10.369
questions, get the news and
weather.

01:13:10.369 --> 01:13:14.849
&gt;&gt; They call it a personal
assistant, and just that term

01:13:14.849 --> 01:13:19.360
implies this intimate connection
that we then begin to develop

01:13:19.360 --> 01:13:20.360
with Amazon.

01:13:20.360 --> 01:13:22.909
&gt;&gt; Alexa, sing the ABC song.

01:13:22.909 --> 01:13:26.349
&gt;&gt; ♪ A, B, C, D, E, F...

01:13:26.349 --> 01:13:28.769
♪
&gt;&gt; I believe that when we think

01:13:28.769 --> 01:13:32.949
about the future and the future
with artificial intelligence,

01:13:32.949 --> 01:13:37.419
given where we currently are
today, Alexa in some ways

01:13:37.419 --> 01:13:40.419
represents the moment that it
becomes seamlessly interwoven

01:13:40.419 --> 01:13:42.100
with our lives.

01:13:42.100 --> 01:13:44.080
&gt;&gt; Alexa, how many teaspoons are

01:13:44.080 --> 01:13:45.080
in a tablespoon?

01:13:45.080 --> 01:13:46.349
&gt;&gt; One tablespoon equals three

01:13:46.349 --> 01:13:47.349
teaspoons.

01:13:47.349 --> 01:13:48.349
&gt;&gt; Oh, okay.

01:13:48.349 --> 01:13:52.679
&gt;&gt; And the problem is that we
forget that it's there.

01:13:52.679 --> 01:13:54.399
&gt;&gt; Alexa, lights on.

01:13:54.399 --> 01:13:55.399
&gt;&gt; Okay.

01:13:55.399 --> 01:13:59.349
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: But Alexa is also
listening-- and she's learning.

01:13:59.349 --> 01:14:01.940
&gt;&gt; I'm answering questions and
learning more.

01:14:01.940 --> 01:14:05.300
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: And that helps
Amazon in the race to dominate

01:14:05.300 --> 01:14:06.830
artificial intelligence.

01:14:06.830 --> 01:14:07.830
&gt;&gt; Alexa...

01:14:07.830 --> 01:14:10.719
&gt;&gt; Every time you ask Alexa
something, you're making the

01:14:10.719 --> 01:14:11.919
Alexa algorithm better.

01:14:11.919 --> 01:14:13.429
It's one of the reasons why

01:14:13.429 --> 01:14:16.329
Amazon, having had a head start,
is able to kind of preserve that

01:14:16.329 --> 01:14:19.800
head start, because they've got
the most data of anyone.

01:14:19.800 --> 01:14:24.280
&gt;&gt; Alexa is one more way for
Amazon to gather extremely

01:14:24.280 --> 01:14:25.309
valuable data.

01:14:25.309 --> 01:14:26.729
And this data collection is

01:14:26.729 --> 01:14:29.130
extremely important to this
business model.

01:14:29.130 --> 01:14:32.439
It's extremely hard to do, and,
you know, convincing people to

01:14:32.439 --> 01:14:35.250
just deploy something like this
in their home is a brilliant

01:14:35.250 --> 01:14:36.439
trick.

01:14:36.439 --> 01:14:38.210
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Dave Limp is

01:14:38.210 --> 01:14:40.879
Amazon's head of devices.

01:14:40.879 --> 01:14:42.119
&gt;&gt; How is it that you

01:14:42.119 --> 01:14:45.840
convinced tens of millions of
people to put what is

01:14:45.840 --> 01:14:48.459
essentially a, a listening
device in their homes?

01:14:48.459 --> 01:14:51.999
&gt;&gt; Well, I, I would first
disagree with the premise.

01:14:51.999 --> 01:14:53.860
It doesn't, it's not a
listening device.

01:14:53.860 --> 01:14:57.419
The, the device in its core
is...

01:14:57.419 --> 01:14:58.530
It has a detector on it.

01:14:58.530 --> 01:14:59.650
We call it internally a

01:14:59.650 --> 01:15:01.150
"wake-word engine."

01:15:01.150 --> 01:15:02.469
And that detector is

01:15:02.469 --> 01:15:05.369
listening-- not really
listening-- it's detecting one

01:15:05.369 --> 01:15:09.949
thing and one thing only, which
is the word you've said that you

01:15:09.949 --> 01:15:11.960
want to get the attention of
that Echo.

01:15:11.960 --> 01:15:16.610
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Once the device is
awake and the blue light is on,

01:15:16.610 --> 01:15:17.610
it's recording.

01:15:17.610 --> 01:15:19.469
And last year, it was revealed

01:15:19.469 --> 01:15:23.280
that Amazon employs thousands of
people around the world to

01:15:23.280 --> 01:15:26.769
listen and transcribe some of
those recordings to help train

01:15:26.769 --> 01:15:27.959
the system.

01:15:27.959 --> 01:15:28.959
&gt;&gt; Do you think that you

01:15:28.959 --> 01:15:31.729
did a good enough job of
disclosing that to consumers?

01:15:31.729 --> 01:15:35.349
That, that there are humans
involved in listening to these

01:15:35.349 --> 01:15:36.510
recordings?

01:15:36.510 --> 01:15:39.409
&gt;&gt; We, we try to articulate what

01:15:39.409 --> 01:15:41.979
we're doing with our products as
clearly as we can.

01:15:41.979 --> 01:15:46.329
But if I could go back in time,
and I could be more clear, and

01:15:46.329 --> 01:15:51.229
the team could be more clear, on
how we were using human beings

01:15:51.229 --> 01:15:55.380
to annotate a small percentage
of the data, I would, for sure.

01:15:55.380 --> 01:15:57.610
What I would say, though, is
that once we realized that

01:15:57.610 --> 01:16:00.219
customers didn't clearly
understand this, and within a

01:16:00.219 --> 01:16:02.729
couple of days, we added an
opt-out feature, so that

01:16:02.729 --> 01:16:06.550
customers could turn off
annotation if they, if they so

01:16:06.550 --> 01:16:07.550
chose.

01:16:07.550 --> 01:16:09.159
And then within a month or two

01:16:09.159 --> 01:16:11.720
later, we allowed people to
auto-delete data, which they

01:16:11.720 --> 01:16:14.059
also asked for within that,
within that time frame.

01:16:14.059 --> 01:16:16.440
You know, we're not going to
always be perfect, but when we

01:16:16.440 --> 01:16:19.290
make mistakes, I think the key
is that we correct them very

01:16:19.290 --> 01:16:21.429
quickly on behalf of customers.

01:16:21.429 --> 01:16:23.150
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: But even one of the

01:16:23.150 --> 01:16:27.139
founders of Amazon Web Services
approaches his Alexa devices

01:16:27.139 --> 01:16:28.629
with caution.

01:16:28.629 --> 01:16:29.629
&gt;&gt; When do you turn off

01:16:29.629 --> 01:16:30.629
your Alexa?

01:16:30.629 --> 01:16:32.840
&gt;&gt; I turn off my Alexa when I

01:16:32.840 --> 01:16:36.630
know for a fact that the
conversation that I am going to

01:16:36.630 --> 01:16:41.170
have, or, or whenever I just
want to have a private moment.

01:16:41.170 --> 01:16:44.679
I don't want certain
conversations to be heard by

01:16:44.679 --> 01:16:49.440
humans, conversations that I
know for a fact are not things

01:16:49.440 --> 01:16:53.909
that should not be shared, then
I actually turn off those

01:16:53.909 --> 01:16:57.820
particular listening devices.

01:16:57.820 --> 01:16:59.469
&gt;&gt; We have had an incredible

01:16:59.469 --> 01:17:00.469
year.

01:17:00.469 --> 01:17:01.469
The team has invented a lot on

01:17:01.469 --> 01:17:04.690
behalf of customers, and I
cannot wait to show you what we

01:17:04.690 --> 01:17:05.690
have.

01:17:05.690 --> 01:17:06.690
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: So far, Limp and

01:17:06.690 --> 01:17:09.260
his team have made Alexa
compatible with more than

01:17:09.260 --> 01:17:11.570
100,000 products.

01:17:11.570 --> 01:17:13.739
&gt;&gt; Echo Frames allow you to get

01:17:13.739 --> 01:17:17.659
done more around you and be more
present in the everyday.

01:17:17.659 --> 01:17:21.150
&gt;&gt; Now they're going to know
more about you than anyone

01:17:21.150 --> 01:17:22.150
knows.

01:17:22.150 --> 01:17:24.729
They're trying to move as

01:17:24.729 --> 01:17:29.499
intimately as possible and as
quietly as possible into

01:17:29.499 --> 01:17:31.300
everyday life.

01:17:31.300 --> 01:17:33.869
&gt;&gt; Echo Loop is a smart ring,

01:17:33.869 --> 01:17:37.829
packed with ways to stay on top
of your day.

01:17:37.829 --> 01:17:42.419
&gt;&gt; Amazon wants to have the
entire environment essentially

01:17:42.419 --> 01:17:43.419
miked.

01:17:43.419 --> 01:17:44.820
&gt;&gt; Alexa, start my running

01:17:44.820 --> 01:17:45.820
playlist.

01:17:45.820 --> 01:17:47.809
&gt;&gt; They want your walk in the

01:17:47.809 --> 01:17:51.059
park, they want your run down
the city street.

01:17:51.059 --> 01:17:54.409
&gt;&gt; Nationwide's teamed up with
Amazon to bring you the all-new

01:17:54.409 --> 01:17:55.409
Echo Auto.

01:17:55.409 --> 01:17:56.579
&gt;&gt; They want what you do in your

01:17:56.579 --> 01:17:59.619
car, they want what you do in
your home.

01:17:59.619 --> 01:18:00.619
&gt;&gt; Amazon Smart Oven.

01:18:00.619 --> 01:18:02.619
&gt;&gt; Alexa, bake for 30 minutes at

01:18:02.619 --> 01:18:03.619
350 degrees.

01:18:03.619 --> 01:18:04.619
(oven beeps)

01:18:04.619 --> 01:18:07.489
&gt;&gt; All these intimacies, all
this insight is being

01:18:07.489 --> 01:18:11.369
integrated, analyzed and
integrated.

01:18:11.369 --> 01:18:14.040
&gt;&gt; Alexa, alarm off.

01:18:14.040 --> 01:18:16.059
&gt;&gt; That is an extraordinary kind

01:18:16.059 --> 01:18:19.760
of power that has never before
existed.

01:18:19.760 --> 01:18:23.739
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: After Alexa, Amazon
would go on to spend nearly a

01:18:23.739 --> 01:18:25.150
billion dollars to buy Ring...

01:18:25.150 --> 01:18:26.409
&gt;&gt; Hey, bud, the police are on

01:18:26.409 --> 01:18:27.409
the way.

01:18:27.409 --> 01:18:28.829
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: A doorbell camera

01:18:28.829 --> 01:18:32.920
and app that Amazon describes as
"the new neighborhood watch."

01:18:32.920 --> 01:18:33.920
&gt;&gt; Hey, get away!

01:18:33.920 --> 01:18:34.920
&gt;&gt; Get out of there!

01:18:34.920 --> 01:18:38.719
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: To promote it,
Amazon has enlisted the help of

01:18:38.719 --> 01:18:40.579
hundreds of local police
departments.

01:18:40.579 --> 01:18:44.400
&gt;&gt; It's a phenomenal tool to
assist detectives.

01:18:44.400 --> 01:18:47.289
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: They give them
access to a portal to request

01:18:47.289 --> 01:18:52.369
footage and have given free
cameras to hand out-- and

01:18:52.369 --> 01:18:53.650
talking points.

01:18:53.650 --> 01:18:55.650
&gt;&gt; This system is so simple to

01:18:55.650 --> 01:18:56.650
use...

01:18:56.650 --> 01:18:57.829
&gt;&gt; You have Amazon in

01:18:57.829 --> 01:19:00.290
partnership with police
departments, who have basically

01:19:00.290 --> 01:19:04.999
turned policemen into, like,
Avon salespeople for Amazon

01:19:04.999 --> 01:19:06.459
Ring.

01:19:06.459 --> 01:19:08.039
They have given police

01:19:08.039 --> 01:19:12.929
departments talking points and
marketing materials to encourage

01:19:12.929 --> 01:19:16.979
the installation of Ring by
community residents.

01:19:16.979 --> 01:19:18.929
None of this was public
knowledge.

01:19:18.929 --> 01:19:25.210
&gt;&gt; And this is Ring's first
indoor cam.

01:19:25.210 --> 01:19:26.760
It is... cute, is what I would
say.

01:19:26.760 --> 01:19:28.809
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Amazon has
continued to expand the scope

01:19:28.809 --> 01:19:30.340
of Ring.

01:19:30.340 --> 01:19:32.170
Last fall, Dave Limp unveiled a

01:19:32.170 --> 01:19:36.710
version designed to monitor the
inside of people's homes.

01:19:36.710 --> 01:19:39.919
Within weeks, hackers discovered
a way to terrorize Ring

01:19:39.919 --> 01:19:56.459
customers.

01:19:56.459 --> 01:19:57.459
&gt;&gt; Did you see that

01:19:57.459 --> 01:19:58.459
video?

01:19:58.459 --> 01:19:59.459
&gt;&gt; I did see that video.

01:19:59.459 --> 01:20:00.459
&gt;&gt; What did you think of
it?

01:20:00.459 --> 01:20:02.969
&gt;&gt; I think that that is a
industry problem.

01:20:02.969 --> 01:20:07.469
It's not just about the, a Ring
camera-- it could be about

01:20:07.469 --> 01:20:08.469
anybody's cameras.

01:20:08.469 --> 01:20:11.260
It's about any device in that...

01:20:11.260 --> 01:20:14.579
And we've already investigated
that one to make sure what, what

01:20:14.579 --> 01:20:16.169
the root cause was.

01:20:16.169 --> 01:20:17.550
What we want to be able to do

01:20:17.550 --> 01:20:19.550
in those cases is, we want to
minimize them.

01:20:19.550 --> 01:20:20.750
We'd like to detect them.

01:20:20.750 --> 01:20:22.079
And we also want to build tools

01:20:22.079 --> 01:20:25.360
that give them the ability so
that doesn't... that, that makes

01:20:25.360 --> 01:20:27.820
it harder for those kinds of
attacks to happen.

01:20:27.820 --> 01:20:29.829
There's a lot of bad people in
this world.

01:20:29.829 --> 01:20:32.909
&gt;&gt; Here's a device that
you had described as cute and

01:20:32.909 --> 01:20:37.219
seems harmless, and I'm just
wondering whether you're being

01:20:37.219 --> 01:20:41.130
straight with people about the
attendant risks to your

01:20:41.130 --> 01:20:44.539
customers that you are obsessed
with, supposedly.

01:20:44.539 --> 01:20:47.469
&gt;&gt; Well, it's not supposedly, we
are obsessed with customers.

01:20:47.469 --> 01:20:51.320
I, I would say that we are
trying to build security

01:20:51.320 --> 01:20:56.570
features at every level of the
stack: operating systems,

01:20:56.570 --> 01:20:59.630
authentication, fraud detection.

01:20:59.630 --> 01:21:01.559
We offer things that customers

01:21:01.559 --> 01:21:04.909
can turn on that make it even,
make it even harder for those

01:21:04.909 --> 01:21:05.909
attacks to happen.

01:21:05.909 --> 01:21:06.909
&gt;&gt; Yo, what's up, how's your

01:21:06.909 --> 01:21:07.909
day?

01:21:07.909 --> 01:21:08.909
&gt;&gt; Who is that?

01:21:08.909 --> 01:21:09.909
&gt;&gt; What's going on, buddy?

01:21:09.909 --> 01:21:11.769
What are you watching?

01:21:11.769 --> 01:21:15.610
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: There were a series
of similar attacks across the

01:21:15.610 --> 01:21:16.610
country.

01:21:16.610 --> 01:21:17.610
&gt;&gt; What's up, homie?

01:21:17.610 --> 01:21:18.610
I still see you.

01:21:18.610 --> 01:21:19.610
&gt;&gt; You hungry?

01:21:19.610 --> 01:21:21.079
&gt;&gt; What's going on, my main man
Shaq?

01:21:21.079 --> 01:21:23.310
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: And it's not just
hackers.

01:21:23.310 --> 01:21:26.729
Ring has fired some of its own
employees for spying on

01:21:26.729 --> 01:21:27.849
customers.

01:21:27.849 --> 01:21:28.989
&gt;&gt; In George Orwell's

01:21:28.989 --> 01:21:33.590
"1984," he describes a dystopia
in which, "You had to live, you

01:21:33.590 --> 01:21:37.499
did live from habit that became
instinct in the assumption that

01:21:37.499 --> 01:21:40.929
every sound you made was
overheard."

01:21:40.929 --> 01:21:45.829
And I wonder if you ever think
about how easily this could

01:21:45.829 --> 01:21:48.179
become dystopian to some degree?

01:21:48.179 --> 01:21:49.300
&gt;&gt; Well, I don't want to live in

01:21:49.300 --> 01:21:50.300
that world.

01:21:50.300 --> 01:21:52.159
So, I do not want to invent the

01:21:52.159 --> 01:21:55.659
technology that, or have my
teams invent the technology that

01:21:55.659 --> 01:21:57.409
would create that world.

01:21:57.409 --> 01:21:59.590
And so... but I am an optimist.

01:21:59.590 --> 01:22:04.489
I, I think if you take the, the
absolute view of that, we

01:22:04.489 --> 01:22:05.659
wouldn't invent anything.

01:22:05.659 --> 01:22:06.659
&gt;&gt; We're increasingly

01:22:06.659 --> 01:22:11.849
living in a world in which your
products and your designs are

01:22:11.849 --> 01:22:12.849
there.

01:22:12.849 --> 01:22:13.849
Do, can you see how it could be

01:22:13.849 --> 01:22:17.019
concerning in some ways that we
all can't opt out of that world

01:22:17.019 --> 01:22:18.019
at this point?

01:22:18.019 --> 01:22:20.050
&gt;&gt; Oh, sure, I can see why it

01:22:20.050 --> 01:22:21.969
could be concerning to some
customers.

01:22:21.969 --> 01:22:26.159
Our job in building that
technology is to build it in

01:22:26.159 --> 01:22:29.249
such a way that it, that it
takes into account for the

01:22:29.249 --> 01:22:32.889
scenarios that you just talked
about, as best as we possibly

01:22:32.889 --> 01:22:33.889
can.

01:22:33.889 --> 01:22:35.909
You know, the, the reality of it

01:22:35.909 --> 01:22:42.599
is, that world happened way
before Ring or Alexa.

01:22:42.599 --> 01:22:45.909
♪ ♪
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: That's something

01:22:45.909 --> 01:22:49.929
that Bezos himself wrestled with
20 years ago.

01:22:49.929 --> 01:22:52.840
&gt;&gt; I believe that privacy is
going to be one of the prominent

01:22:52.840 --> 01:22:53.849
issues of the 21st century.

01:22:53.849 --> 01:22:55.119
The thing is, there are towns

01:22:55.119 --> 01:22:57.550
now in the United States that
have installed security cameras

01:22:57.550 --> 01:23:00.510
on every corner, and their
crime rates decreased by 80%,

01:23:00.510 --> 01:23:03.699
but do you really want cameras
on every corner?

01:23:03.699 --> 01:23:06.649
There are very strange things
that are going to happen over

01:23:06.649 --> 01:23:09.309
the next 100 years with respect
to technology that are going to

01:23:09.309 --> 01:23:13.159
challenge us as a society to
figure out how we want to deal

01:23:13.159 --> 01:23:14.159
with privacy.

01:23:14.159 --> 01:23:15.340
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Decades later,

01:23:15.340 --> 01:23:19.019
Bezos would be at the vanguard
of expanding the use of that

01:23:19.019 --> 01:23:21.769
kind of technology.

01:23:21.769 --> 01:23:22.769
&gt;&gt; Introducing Amazon

01:23:22.769 --> 01:23:24.459
Rekognition Video.

01:23:24.459 --> 01:23:26.139
&gt;&gt; Rekognition allows you to

01:23:26.139 --> 01:23:27.519
pass an image to us.

01:23:27.519 --> 01:23:29.840
You can say, "Do these two faces

01:23:29.840 --> 01:23:30.840
match?"

01:23:30.840 --> 01:23:31.840
Which is incredibly useful for

01:23:31.840 --> 01:23:34.449
applications in the security
space.

01:23:34.449 --> 01:23:35.449
You can imagine...

01:23:35.449 --> 01:23:36.449
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: After Amazon rolled

01:23:36.449 --> 01:23:39.989
out a facial recognition tool,
it marketed it to law

01:23:39.989 --> 01:23:41.769
enforcement.

01:23:41.769 --> 01:23:42.789
&gt;&gt; Recognize and track persons

01:23:42.789 --> 01:23:47.129
of interest from a collection
of tens of millions of faces.

01:23:47.129 --> 01:23:50.979
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Police we've spoken
to say it's a valuable tool to

01:23:50.979 --> 01:23:52.560
identify suspects quickly.

01:23:52.560 --> 01:23:53.800
&gt;&gt; ...appears to be a match, but

01:23:53.800 --> 01:23:55.669
I'm gonna make sure I look at
them all.

01:23:55.669 --> 01:23:58.340
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: And while Amazon
has offered guidelines for how

01:23:58.340 --> 01:24:01.969
it should be used, there are few
laws governing the use of this

01:24:01.969 --> 01:24:02.969
technology.

01:24:02.969 --> 01:24:03.969
&gt;&gt; It returns anybody with

01:24:03.969 --> 01:24:05.519
warrants that look like her.

01:24:05.519 --> 01:24:06.519
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Civil liberties

01:24:06.519 --> 01:24:11.130
advocates have raised concerns,
as have computer scientists, who

01:24:11.130 --> 01:24:15.019
worry Amazon has released the
software before it's ready, and

01:24:15.019 --> 01:24:18.439
that police are essentially
field-testing it on the public

01:24:18.439 --> 01:24:20.969
on behalf of the company.

01:24:20.969 --> 01:24:23.479
&gt;&gt; The tools are not what I call

01:24:23.479 --> 01:24:25.159
battle-tested.

01:24:25.159 --> 01:24:27.669
And we still do not understand

01:24:27.669 --> 01:24:31.469
how well they work in the
environments in which they'll be

01:24:31.469 --> 01:24:32.469
applied.

01:24:32.469 --> 01:24:34.279
That's where I see a danger.

01:24:34.279 --> 01:24:37.699
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Anima Anandkumar
was the principal scientist for

01:24:37.699 --> 01:24:40.429
artificial intelligence at
Amazon.

01:24:40.429 --> 01:24:43.690
In her first interview about her
concerns she told us she was

01:24:43.690 --> 01:24:47.380
particularly alarmed by an
M.I.T. study that found the

01:24:47.380 --> 01:24:52.510
software prone to mistakes with
darker-skinned faces.

01:24:52.510 --> 01:24:55.989
Amazon has questioned the
study's methodology.

01:24:55.989 --> 01:24:59.190
&gt;&gt; As a researcher in A.I., I
feel it's my personal

01:24:59.190 --> 01:25:03.690
responsibility to educate the
public of where A.I. truly is

01:25:03.690 --> 01:25:04.789
today, right?

01:25:04.789 --> 01:25:06.389
Because they hear so much of

01:25:06.389 --> 01:25:09.889
A.I. being hyped up, you know,
it's supposed to be magical,

01:25:09.889 --> 01:25:12.310
it's supposed to solve all the
world's problems.

01:25:12.310 --> 01:25:15.500
I see the potential in doing
that, but at the same time we

01:25:15.500 --> 01:25:16.790
need a reality check.

01:25:16.790 --> 01:25:19.090
We need to ask, where is A.I.

01:25:19.090 --> 01:25:20.090
today?

01:25:20.090 --> 01:25:21.389
What can it truly do well?

01:25:21.389 --> 01:25:23.780
&gt;&gt; And when it comes to
facial recognition, you don't

01:25:23.780 --> 01:25:25.959
think it's ready for primetime.

01:25:25.959 --> 01:25:26.959
&gt;&gt; I don't think face

01:25:26.959 --> 01:25:30.469
recognition is ready for
primetime in challenging

01:25:30.469 --> 01:25:32.800
applications like law
enforcement.

01:25:32.800 --> 01:25:35.889
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Anandkumar and
other scientists have asked

01:25:35.889 --> 01:25:39.469
Amazon to stop selling
Rekognition to law enforcement

01:25:39.469 --> 01:25:42.849
because they say the system's
accuracy is still in question,

01:25:42.849 --> 01:25:47.469
and there are no clear
regulations about how it's used.

01:25:47.469 --> 01:25:49.370
We asked Andy Jassy about it.

01:25:49.370 --> 01:25:52.929
&gt;&gt; I have a different view, and

01:25:52.929 --> 01:25:53.929
we've spent...

01:25:53.929 --> 01:25:54.929
We've had the facial

01:25:54.929 --> 01:25:58.349
recognition technology out for
use for over two-and-a-half

01:25:58.349 --> 01:25:59.400
years now.

01:25:59.400 --> 01:26:00.659
And in those two-and-a-half

01:26:00.659 --> 01:26:03.309
years, we've never had any
reported misuse of law

01:26:03.309 --> 01:26:06.079
enforcement using the facial
recognition technology and, you

01:26:06.079 --> 01:26:08.840
know, I think a lot of societal
good is already being done with

01:26:08.840 --> 01:26:10.219
facial recognition technology.

01:26:10.219 --> 01:26:12.269
Already, you've seen hundreds of

01:26:12.269 --> 01:26:15.269
missing kids reunited with their
parents, and hundreds of human

01:26:15.269 --> 01:26:19.469
trafficking victims saved, and
all kinds of security and

01:26:19.469 --> 01:26:22.219
identity and education uses, so
there's a lot of good that's

01:26:22.219 --> 01:26:23.659
been done with it.

01:26:23.659 --> 01:26:25.309
But I also understand that it

01:26:25.309 --> 01:26:26.309
could be misused.

01:26:26.309 --> 01:26:27.472
And I think at the end of the

01:26:27.472 --> 01:26:29.769
day with any technology, whether
you're talking about facial

01:26:29.769 --> 01:26:32.959
recognition technology or
anything else, the people that

01:26:32.959 --> 01:26:36.030
use the technology have to be
responsible for it, and if they

01:26:36.030 --> 01:26:38.379
use it irresponsibly, they have
to be held accountable.

01:26:38.379 --> 01:26:40.300
&gt;&gt; There's been all
sorts of problems with policing

01:26:40.300 --> 01:26:41.300
in this country.

01:26:41.300 --> 01:26:42.320
So why allow police departments

01:26:42.320 --> 01:26:43.530
to experiment?

01:26:43.530 --> 01:26:45.150
&gt;&gt; We believe that governments

01:26:45.150 --> 01:26:47.749
and the organizations that are
charged with keeping our

01:26:47.749 --> 01:26:51.110
communities safe have to have
access to the most

01:26:51.110 --> 01:26:53.719
sophisticated, modern
technology that exists.

01:26:53.719 --> 01:26:55.800
We don't have a large number of
police departments that are

01:26:55.800 --> 01:26:58.619
using our facial recognition
technology, and as I said,

01:26:58.619 --> 01:27:01.369
we've never received any
complaints of misuse.

01:27:01.369 --> 01:27:04.099
Let's see if somehow they abuse
the technology.

01:27:04.099 --> 01:27:07.979
They haven't done that, and to
assume that they're gonna do it

01:27:07.979 --> 01:27:09.919
and therefore you shouldn't
allow them to have access to the

01:27:09.919 --> 01:27:12.059
most sophisticated technology
out there, doesn't feel like the

01:27:12.059 --> 01:27:13.559
right balance to me.

01:27:13.559 --> 01:27:14.559
&gt;&gt; It's been difficult

01:27:14.559 --> 01:27:17.459
to even know how many police
departments are using the facial

01:27:17.459 --> 01:27:20.769
recognition technology, and
there's no public auditing to

01:27:20.769 --> 01:27:23.849
know whether there are
complaints about abuse.

01:27:23.849 --> 01:27:25.510
How would the public ever know?

01:27:25.510 --> 01:27:28.209
&gt;&gt; You know, again, I don't

01:27:28.209 --> 01:27:31.360
think we know the total number
of police departments that are

01:27:31.360 --> 01:27:33.789
using facial recognition
technology.

01:27:33.789 --> 01:27:39.090
I mean, there's, you can use any
number-- we have 165 services in

01:27:39.090 --> 01:27:41.649
our technology infrastructure
platform, and you can use them

01:27:41.649 --> 01:27:44.769
in whatever conjunction, any
combination that you want.

01:27:44.769 --> 01:27:49.399
We know of some, and the vast
majority of those that are using

01:27:49.399 --> 01:27:52.690
it are using it according to the
guidance that we've prescribed.

01:27:52.690 --> 01:27:55.519
And when they're not, we have
conversations, and if we find

01:27:55.519 --> 01:27:57.499
that they're using it in some
irresponsible way, we won't

01:27:57.499 --> 01:28:01.260
allow them to use the service
and the platform.

01:28:01.260 --> 01:28:03.780
♪ ♪
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Andy Jassy and Jeff

01:28:03.780 --> 01:28:06.349
Bezos have said they want
governments to hurry up and

01:28:06.349 --> 01:28:10.579
regulate how law enforcement can
