01:42:32.989 --> 01:42:35.179
&gt;&gt; Here's Bezos achieving this

01:42:35.179 --> 01:42:37.369
American dream and success.

01:42:37.369 --> 01:42:40.379
And, and he's now the target of,

01:42:40.379 --> 01:42:41.909
of all of this criticism.

01:42:41.909 --> 01:42:43.670
And basically, it becomes a

01:42:43.670 --> 01:42:45.999
symbol of all of his problems.

01:42:45.999 --> 01:42:47.999
&gt;&gt; Amazon is closing 30% of

01:42:47.999 --> 01:42:49.340
America's stores and malls and
paying...

01:42:49.340 --> 01:42:52.899
&gt;&gt; You're basically a piñata
dangling in front of any

01:42:52.899 --> 01:42:54.940
politician with a populist
message.

01:42:54.940 --> 01:42:57.800
Anyone who wants to talk about
wealth inequality, they're

01:42:57.800 --> 01:42:59.030
pointing their finger at you.

01:42:59.030 --> 01:43:01.639
&gt;&gt; This is why three people own

01:43:01.639 --> 01:43:04.070
more wealth than the bottom
half.

01:43:04.070 --> 01:43:06.510
&gt;&gt; If they want to talk about
problems with capitalism in

01:43:06.510 --> 01:43:08.280
general, they're pointing their
finger at you.

01:43:08.280 --> 01:43:12.499
&gt;&gt; We need to enforce our
antitrust laws, break up these

01:43:12.499 --> 01:43:14.570
giant companies.

01:43:14.570 --> 01:43:16.639
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: And it's coming

01:43:16.639 --> 01:43:18.649
from all sides.

01:43:18.649 --> 01:43:19.649
&gt;&gt; President Trump just sent a

01:43:19.649 --> 01:43:22.010
chill down the spine of Jeff
Bezos...

01:43:22.010 --> 01:43:26.570
&gt;&gt; The president again teed off
against Amazon on Twitter.

01:43:26.570 --> 01:43:30.539
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: President Trump has
made Bezos's ownership of "The

01:43:30.539 --> 01:43:32.709
Washington Post" a regular
target.

01:43:32.709 --> 01:43:36.889
&gt;&gt; "Washington Post," Bezos uses
that as his lobbyist, okay?

01:43:36.889 --> 01:43:39.709
&gt;&gt; He kind of assumed that "The
Washington Post" was operated in

01:43:39.709 --> 01:43:43.429
the sort of way that he would
operate a newspaper.

01:43:43.429 --> 01:43:47.010
And so he thought that Bezos was
dictating coverage to the

01:43:47.010 --> 01:43:51.139
"Post," which we should be
careful to say is not the case.

01:43:51.139 --> 01:43:55.349
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Trump has also
criticized Amazon, and accused

01:43:55.349 --> 01:43:57.840
the company of evading taxes.

01:43:57.840 --> 01:44:00.670
Last year, the company was

01:44:00.670 --> 01:44:04.159
competing for a $10 billion
cloud computing contract with

01:44:04.159 --> 01:44:05.929
the Department of Defense.

01:44:05.929 --> 01:44:06.929
&gt;&gt; This contract would have

01:44:06.929 --> 01:44:10.349
solidified Bezos's dominance in
cloud computing.

01:44:10.349 --> 01:44:12.949
This is a hugely important
thing.

01:44:12.949 --> 01:44:14.969
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: But the company
claims President Trump

01:44:14.969 --> 01:44:17.129
intervened to scuttle the deal.

01:44:17.129 --> 01:44:18.270
&gt;&gt; And we're looking at it very

01:44:18.270 --> 01:44:19.270
seriously.

01:44:19.270 --> 01:44:20.270
It's a very big contract.

01:44:20.270 --> 01:44:23.129
One of the biggest ever given.

01:44:23.129 --> 01:44:24.159
&gt;&gt; A big win for Microsoft,

01:44:24.159 --> 01:44:25.290
beating out Amazon...

01:44:25.290 --> 01:44:27.050
&gt;&gt; Amazon can protest the

01:44:27.050 --> 01:44:31.169
outcome, especially given the
unusual, unprecedented comments

01:44:31.169 --> 01:44:32.929
by President Trump...

01:44:32.929 --> 01:44:34.369
&gt;&gt; It's an extraordinary times

01:44:34.369 --> 01:44:37.489
we live in that one of the
world's biggest corporations,

01:44:37.489 --> 01:44:40.439
Amazon, is now saying, "The
president of the United States

01:44:40.439 --> 01:44:42.729
has corrupted our ability to win
this contract."

01:44:42.729 --> 01:44:44.309
&gt;&gt; Is there any evidence
of that?

01:44:44.309 --> 01:44:48.269
&gt;&gt; The evidence is what the
president has publicly said.

01:44:48.269 --> 01:44:52.119
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: And Amazon's
problems have continued to

01:44:52.119 --> 01:44:54.289
multiply.

01:44:54.289 --> 01:44:55.619
The Federal Trade Commission is

01:44:55.619 --> 01:45:00.079
now reconsidering its stance on
antitrust enforcement and is

01:45:00.079 --> 01:45:04.909
looking at Amazon-- as are
regulators in the E.U.

01:45:04.909 --> 01:45:08.119
&gt;&gt; This gatekeeper power and how
the platforms are exercising it

01:45:08.119 --> 01:45:09.889
is of tremendous concern.

01:45:09.889 --> 01:45:11.599
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: In Washington,

01:45:11.599 --> 01:45:14.879
Democratic Congressman David
Cicilline has launched an

01:45:14.879 --> 01:45:18.969
antitrust investigation into
allegations of abusive conduct

01:45:18.969 --> 01:45:22.530
by Amazon and the other tech
giants.

01:45:22.530 --> 01:45:25.039
&gt;&gt; Given your experience, do you
agree with Amazon's statements

01:45:25.039 --> 01:45:28.269
suggesting that it seeks to act
in the best interest of

01:45:28.269 --> 01:45:29.489
independent sellers?

01:45:29.489 --> 01:45:30.849
&gt;&gt; I disagree with that.

01:45:30.849 --> 01:45:33.440
We get, I don't know, what I
might call bullying with a

01:45:33.440 --> 01:45:34.440
smile.

01:45:34.440 --> 01:45:35.440
&gt;&gt; We were able to get several

01:45:35.440 --> 01:45:37.400
C.E.Os. to come to a public
hearing.

01:45:37.400 --> 01:45:43.380
That required tremendous courage
because there's a real potential

01:45:43.380 --> 01:45:47.129
for economic retaliation for
their sharing that.

01:45:47.129 --> 01:45:49.369
&gt;&gt; We don't have the resources
to fight Amazon.

01:45:49.369 --> 01:45:52.349
We could use some help.

01:45:52.349 --> 01:45:53.349
&gt;&gt; In the course of your

01:45:53.349 --> 01:45:55.719
investigation thus far, and
you've had several public

01:45:55.719 --> 01:45:59.619
hearings, have you seen any
evidence of anti-competitive

01:45:59.619 --> 01:46:01.309
behavior by Amazon?

01:46:01.309 --> 01:46:03.059
&gt;&gt; Um, we have seen evidence of

01:46:03.059 --> 01:46:07.320
anti-competitive behavior by all
of the large platforms as a

01:46:07.320 --> 01:46:08.849
result of their market
dominance.

01:46:08.849 --> 01:46:11.829
But it sort of doesn't fall on
the companies to fix this

01:46:11.829 --> 01:46:12.829
problem.

01:46:12.829 --> 01:46:13.829
It falls on us.

01:46:13.829 --> 01:46:15.469
Without objection, the hearing
is adjourned.

01:46:15.469 --> 01:46:18.199
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Cicilline's
committee is considering

01:46:18.199 --> 01:46:21.639
everything from imposing limits
on what businesses a company

01:46:21.639 --> 01:46:25.639
like Amazon can engage in, to
restricting the collection and

01:46:25.639 --> 01:46:29.959
use of data.

01:46:29.959 --> 01:46:30.959
♪ ♪

01:46:30.959 --> 01:46:34.360
The man who helped Jeff Bezos
build Amazon 25 years ago says

01:46:34.360 --> 01:46:36.959
it may be necessary to go even
further.

01:46:36.959 --> 01:46:42.230
&gt;&gt; On the one hand, I'm proud of
what it became, but it also

01:46:42.230 --> 01:46:43.369
scares me.

01:46:43.369 --> 01:46:47.579
And, um, I just feel like it's

01:46:47.579 --> 01:46:56.039
important for someone in my
situation to, you know, at least

01:46:56.039 --> 01:46:59.069
say what they think about what's
going on.

01:46:59.069 --> 01:47:01.329
&gt;&gt; This is sort of in
some ways a baby that you gave

01:47:01.329 --> 01:47:02.559
birth to, right?

01:47:02.559 --> 01:47:04.929
And so, I mean, you helped birth

01:47:04.929 --> 01:47:05.929
Amazon.

01:47:05.929 --> 01:47:07.909
&gt;&gt; Um, yeah, very much so.

01:47:07.909 --> 01:47:10.860
In fact, I used to, um, you
know, get up several times

01:47:10.860 --> 01:47:15.219
during the night to, just to see
if it was working and... and,

01:47:15.219 --> 01:47:18.939
you know, take care of it if it
wasn't, so...

01:47:18.939 --> 01:47:21.690
&gt;&gt; And when you look at
what Amazon has grown into

01:47:21.690 --> 01:47:24.159
today, you see what?

01:47:24.159 --> 01:47:25.619
&gt;&gt; (chuckles)

01:47:25.619 --> 01:47:30.360
Well, um... you know, you
don't want to see your

01:47:30.360 --> 01:47:36.789
offspring, um, become, um,
antisocial adults, right?

01:47:36.789 --> 01:47:40.860
So I think not all of the
effects of the company on the

01:47:40.860 --> 01:47:44.269
world are for the best and,
um...

01:47:44.269 --> 01:47:48.959
And, you know, I, I wish it
weren't so, and I... you know,

01:47:48.959 --> 01:47:51.329
and I... but I had something to
do with bringing it into

01:47:51.329 --> 01:47:53.849
existence, so, it's partly on
me.

01:47:53.849 --> 01:47:55.709
&gt;&gt; And, I mean, isn't...

01:47:55.709 --> 01:47:57.439
Isn't this just capitalism?

01:47:57.439 --> 01:48:00.110
Isn't this just a company doing
what a company does?

01:48:00.110 --> 01:48:01.110
&gt;&gt; Yes.

01:48:01.110 --> 01:48:02.760
Yes, it is, um, and I think

01:48:02.760 --> 01:48:07.840
they're doing what the business
schools teach people to do, and

01:48:07.840 --> 01:48:12.019
they're doing it aggressively
and skillfully and with great

01:48:12.019 --> 01:48:13.439
intelligence.

01:48:13.439 --> 01:48:14.820
And they will continue to do

01:48:14.820 --> 01:48:19.289
that unless they're constrained
by other forces in society.

01:48:19.289 --> 01:48:22.290
&gt;&gt; There are proposals
out there to break up Amazon.

01:48:22.290 --> 01:48:25.669
Is that something you'd promote,
the idea of breaking them up?

01:48:25.669 --> 01:48:28.820
&gt;&gt; Um, I think that they're now
at the scale where that could

01:48:28.820 --> 01:48:31.519
potentially make sense.

01:48:31.519 --> 01:48:33.260
&gt;&gt; How do you and Jeff

01:48:33.260 --> 01:48:36.229
and others at the senior
leadership level think about the

01:48:36.229 --> 01:48:38.299
call to break you guys up?

01:48:38.299 --> 01:48:40.590
&gt;&gt; We don't think about it very,

01:48:40.590 --> 01:48:41.590
very deeply.

01:48:41.590 --> 01:48:42.639
You know, I've been at Amazon

01:48:42.639 --> 01:48:45.430
now for 22-and-a-half years,
and I always remember one of

01:48:45.430 --> 01:48:48.070
the first things I heard Jeff
Bezos say back when we could

01:48:48.070 --> 01:48:50.179
fit the whole company in just
one conference room for an

01:48:50.179 --> 01:48:51.179
all-hands meeting.

01:48:51.179 --> 01:48:52.439
He said, "I would not go to bed

01:48:52.439 --> 01:48:55.170
at night fearing your
competitors or fearing any

01:48:55.170 --> 01:48:56.219
external issues.

01:48:56.219 --> 01:48:57.300
I would go to bed at night

01:48:57.300 --> 01:48:59.639
fearing whether you're doing
right by your customers."

01:48:59.639 --> 01:49:01.849
And that really is a credo that
we live here and it's what we

01:49:01.849 --> 01:49:03.330
spend most of our time thinking
about.

01:49:03.330 --> 01:49:08.080
&gt;&gt; Well, I, I understand that
we're big, and that, that we

01:49:08.080 --> 01:49:11.781
deserve scrutiny, and I think
everything that's... that's

01:49:11.781 --> 01:49:15.179
large in the economy and in
society should deserve scrutiny.

01:49:15.179 --> 01:49:17.510
The problem is, when you think
about us, we're in a lot of

01:49:17.510 --> 01:49:18.709
verticals, yes.

01:49:18.709 --> 01:49:20.969
There's... there's video, and

01:49:20.969 --> 01:49:24.609
there's commerce, and there's,
you know, there's web services--

01:49:24.609 --> 01:49:25.949
there are all these things.

01:49:25.949 --> 01:49:28.270
But in every one of them, we

01:49:28.270 --> 01:49:31.860
have intense competition, and I
do understand why, when you're

01:49:31.860 --> 01:49:35.739
in a lot of them, it can seem
like we're everywhere, but the

01:49:35.739 --> 01:49:36.739
global...

01:49:36.739 --> 01:49:37.739
If we were everywhere, that

01:49:37.739 --> 01:49:39.659
means we're talking about the
global economy, not just global

01:49:39.659 --> 01:49:45.409
retail-- it's so vast, we're
just, you know, we're a speck.

01:49:45.409 --> 01:49:48.979
&gt;&gt; To the public, it may
sound strange coming from

01:49:48.979 --> 01:49:51.669
Amazon, which is a company with
basically a trillion-dollar

01:49:51.669 --> 01:49:55.590
market cap, your C.E.O. is the
richest man in the world, but

01:49:55.590 --> 01:49:58.880
Jeff Wilke said to me that
you're kind of just a speck in

01:49:58.880 --> 01:50:00.630
the scheme of things.

01:50:00.630 --> 01:50:02.110
Do you see how that could seem

01:50:02.110 --> 01:50:04.289
strange or incongruous?

01:50:04.289 --> 01:50:06.820
&gt;&gt; You know, Amazon as a whole

01:50:06.820 --> 01:50:10.960
has become, you know, has been
successful, but simply because

01:50:10.960 --> 01:50:13.789
the company's been successful in
a few different business

01:50:13.789 --> 01:50:17.959
segments doesn't mean it's
somehow too big.

01:50:17.959 --> 01:50:20.619
♪ ♪
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: As Jeff Bezos's

01:50:20.619 --> 01:50:23.619
company is coming under ever
greater scrutiny-- for

01:50:23.619 --> 01:50:27.489
everything from how it wields
power to even its impact on the

01:50:27.489 --> 01:50:31.849
environment-- he's continuing to
look beyond it all.

01:50:31.849 --> 01:50:37.979
&gt;&gt; We get to preserve this
unique gem of a planet which is

01:50:37.979 --> 01:50:38.999
completely irreplaceable.

01:50:38.999 --> 01:50:42.859
There is no plan B.

01:50:42.859 --> 01:50:46.489
We have to save this planet, and
we shouldn't give up a future

01:50:46.489 --> 01:50:49.439
for our grandchildren's
grandchildren of dynamism and

01:50:49.439 --> 01:50:50.439
growth.

01:50:50.439 --> 01:50:52.280
We can have both.

01:50:52.280 --> 01:50:55.489
Who is gonna do this work?

01:50:55.489 --> 01:50:57.169
(rocket rumbling)

01:50:57.169 --> 01:51:00.609
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: He's spending a
billion dollars a year of his

01:51:00.609 --> 01:51:05.429
personal fortune on a space
exploration company he created.

01:51:05.429 --> 01:51:10.130
&gt;&gt; And it's this generation's
job to build that road to space,

01:51:10.130 --> 01:51:14.239
so that the future generations
can unleash their creativity.

01:51:14.239 --> 01:51:19.570
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: For Bezos, it's
always been about one thing: his

01:51:19.570 --> 01:51:20.999
vision for the future.

01:51:20.999 --> 01:51:23.300
&gt;&gt; I want you to think about

01:51:23.300 --> 01:51:24.300
this.

01:51:24.300 --> 01:51:26.050
This vision sounds very big, and

01:51:26.050 --> 01:51:28.489
it is.

01:51:28.489 --> 01:51:30.170
None of this is easy, all of it

01:51:30.170 --> 01:51:35.570
is hard, but I want to inspire
you, and so think about this.

01:51:35.570 --> 01:51:37.090
Big things start small.

01:51:37.090 --> 01:51:38.090
(audience applauding)

01:51:38.090 --> 01:51:39.090
Thank you.

